WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.240
[Amit Varma]: Before you listen to this episode of The Scene and the Unseen, I have a recommendation for

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:09.240
[Amit Varma]: you.

00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:13.440
[Amit Varma]: Do check out Pulya Bazi, hosted by Saurabh Chandra and Pranay Kotesane, two really good

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:14.440
[Amit Varma]: friends of mine.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:16.480
[Amit Varma]: Kick-ass podcast in Hindi.

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:19.040
[Amit Varma]: It's amazing.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:23.120
[Amit Varma]: Imagine that you are the minister in charge of Mumbai breakfast.

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:26.840
[Amit Varma]: All the millions of people in Mumbai want breakfast every morning and you have to make

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:30.540
[Amit Varma]: sure that whatever they want to eat reaches them in time.

00:00:30.540 --> 00:00:35.240
[Amit Varma]: Some people want eggs, some want dosa, horror of horror, some even want poha.

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:36.800
[Amit Varma]: But who are we to judge them?

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:41.840
[Amit Varma]: This means that you have to calibrate egg procurement, dosa batter procurement, poha

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:46.680
[Amit Varma]: procurement, tea and coffee and milk procurement and make sure that everyone gets their breakfast

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:49.040
[Amit Varma]: alright and the system never breaks down.

00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:51.440
[Amit Varma]: Do you think you'd be able to do that planning?

00:00:51.440 --> 00:00:55.560
[Amit Varma]: All the logistics, the thousands of excel sheets, the contingency plans for everything

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:58.480
[Amit Varma]: that could go wrong, is that a job you'd like?

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:03.000
[Amit Varma]: What if you failed at it and the people of Mumbai did not have breakfast for a day?

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:05.280
[Amit Varma]: A city of hungry people.

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:07.920
[Amit Varma]: Sounds like a dystopian nightmare, doesn't it?

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:15.560
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:16.560
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:16.560 --> 00:01:19.560
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.560
[Amit Varma]: The question I just posed is plainly absurd.

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:29.440
[Amit Varma]: No one person or agency can coordinate the logistics involved in producing breakfast

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:32.060
[Amit Varma]: for an entire city and feeding it.

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:34.040
[Amit Varma]: But that doesn't mean that people haven't tried.

00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:38.440
[Amit Varma]: The Soviet Union once attempted to manage a nation's food supplies that way and it led

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:41.320
[Amit Varma]: to famine, starvation and food lines.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:45.560
[Amit Varma]: You cannot, as we now know, plan an economy from the top down.

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:50.360
[Amit Varma]: Mumbai feeds itself because millions of people pursue their own self-interest and manage

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:54.080
[Amit Varma]: to feed themselves by fulfilling each other's needs.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:57.320
[Amit Varma]: Economy works best in a bottom-up way.

00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:02.560
[Amit Varma]: Languages evolve, culture grows, cities form, economies run in a bottom-up way through what

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:05.680
[Amit Varma]: economists call spontaneous order.

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:09.220
[Amit Varma]: And our universe and life itself was formed in a bottom-up way.

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:13.280
[Amit Varma]: What we call spontaneous order can also be called natural selection.

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:14.960
[Amit Varma]: They're basically the same thing.

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:18.800
[Amit Varma]: Processes that lead to intricate and complex mechanisms.

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:21.560
[Amit Varma]: Designs without the need for a designer.

00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:26.560
[Amit Varma]: Because of natural selection, we don't need a god to explain this wonderful complex universe

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:27.560
[Amit Varma]: we live in.

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:32.720
[Amit Varma]: Equally, spontaneous order explains why we do not need government, another false god,

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:35.040
[Amit Varma]: to run an economy or a society.

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:39.100
[Amit Varma]: We do need government, but not to direct things from the top.

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:44.040
[Amit Varma]: And yet, humans tend to instinctively think in top-down ways, to seek command and control,

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:46.240
[Amit Varma]: and resist bottom-up explanations.

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:51.760
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's so absurd that many on the right hold on to the religion of God and deny

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:56.920
[Amit Varma]: natural selection, while many on the left hold on to the religion of government and

00:02:56.920 --> 00:02:58.640
[Amit Varma]: deny spontaneous order.

00:02:58.640 --> 00:03:03.560
[Amit Varma]: They are both making exactly the same creationist mistake.

00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:07.600
[Amit Varma]: My guest for today is Matt Ridley, author of many fine books, including the one we'll

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:11.020
[Amit Varma]: discuss today, The Evolution of Everything.

00:03:11.020 --> 00:03:16.440
[Amit Varma]: In this book, he writes about how the universe, life, culture, language, cities, our brains,

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:21.120
[Amit Varma]: our economies, and even our future, all evolve in a bottom-up way.

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:22.780
[Amit Varma]: And thank God for that.

