[Guest]: Thank you, Amit.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:42.440
[Guest]: It's great to be on the show.

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:47.520
[Amit Varma]: Matt, it's very interesting how humans tend to think of the world in top down ways in

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:49.040
[Amit Varma]: all its different aspects.

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:53.240
[Amit Varma]: We've invented God to explain the universe, whenever we think of something that needs

00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:56.640
[Amit Varma]: to be done, we say, hey, government should do it because someone has to centrally plan

00:04:56.640 --> 00:04:57.840
[Amit Varma]: it and so on.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:01.060
[Amit Varma]: Now, you studied zoology in college.

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:06.840
[Amit Varma]: At what point did you sort of become firstly aware that, you know, the bottoms-up approach

00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:08.720
[Amit Varma]: to the world is a better way of looking at it?

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:14.560
[Amit Varma]: And when did you begin to look at all of the world this way, not just, you know, not just

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:17.200
[Guest]: zoology and not just natural life?

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:18.200
[Guest]: It's a good question.

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:20.640
[Guest]: And I don't really remember when this dawned on me.

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:21.640
[Guest]: It dawned on me gradually.

00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:25.960
[Guest]: It dawned on me in a bottom-up way, perhaps.

00:05:25.960 --> 00:05:31.840
[Guest]: But you're right to say that this for me begins with the natural world, with biological evolution,

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:37.480
[Guest]: natural selection, and Charles Darwin's theory, which I learned first about in school and

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:41.840
[Guest]: then in more detail at university when I studied zoology, as you say.

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:46.800
[Guest]: And I wrote several books about evolution and genetics.

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:52.280
[Guest]: And it became more and more clear to me that there is an incredible complexity in the natural

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:53.280
[Guest]: world.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:58.000
[Guest]: There is an unbelievable complexity in your body and mine as we sit here with trillions

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:05.640
[Guest]: of cells, millions of proteins, tens of thousands of genes, all working in coordination at exactly

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:08.680
[Guest]: the right levels of speed and concentration.

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:09.680
[Guest]: It's mind-boggling.

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:14.760
[Guest]: I mean, it's more complex than any machine that human beings have ever devised or even

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:17.260
[Guest]: could imagine devising.

00:06:17.260 --> 00:06:21.840
[Guest]: And yet we have satisfied ourselves, those of us who understand evolution, and indeed

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:29.840
[Guest]: a large chunk of the world, that this can happen without direction, without creation.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:35.200
[Guest]: And it just struck me relatively recently, actually, just in the last few years, that

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:40.920
[Guest]: we were being equally creationist about the human world as we used to be about the natural

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:41.920
[Guest]: world.

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:46.960
[Guest]: And we were thinking of the complexity of a city.

00:06:46.960 --> 00:06:48.160
[Guest]: We're sitting in Mumbai.

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:49.360
[Guest]: It's an enormous city.

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:50.360
[Guest]: It's incredibly complicated.

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:54.360
[Guest]: Lots of people will have lunch in Mumbai today.

00:06:54.360 --> 00:06:57.840
[Guest]: Who's in charge of making sure they get enough to eat?

00:06:57.840 --> 00:06:59.520
[Guest]: The answer is nobody and everybody.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:01.320
[Guest]: It's a bottom-up system.

00:07:01.320 --> 00:07:02.320
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:06.040
[Amit Varma]: So what I want to do in this episode is really talk about your book, The Evolution of Everything,

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:07.360
[Amit Varma]: which deals exactly with this.

00:07:07.360 --> 00:07:12.360
[Amit Varma]: I'll just quote a sentence from your book so listeners get a sense of what the book

00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:13.360
[Amit Varma]: is about.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:18.000
[Amit Varma]: The way that, quote, the way that human history is taught can therefore mislead because it

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:25.680
[Amit Varma]: places far too much emphasis on design, direction, and planning, and far too little on evolution.

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:26.680
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:28.440
[Amit Varma]: And your book, of course, is called The Evolution of Everything.

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:34.640
[Amit Varma]: And in a series of like 16 chapters, you take readers through essentially starting from

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:39.040
[Amit Varma]: the universe all the way to the internet, talking about how everything in between cultures,

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:42.960
[Amit Varma]: cities, languages, all of them emerge bottom up.

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:47.440
[Amit Varma]: And at best, they can be taught, but, you know, people who try to teach them are making

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:48.440
[Amit Varma]: a mistake.

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:52.040
[Amit Varma]: They can only be learned, as in the case of languages, for example.

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:56.960
[Amit Varma]: So I thought we'll just follow the structure of the book and just go kind of chapter by

00:07:56.960 --> 00:08:00.480
[Amit Varma]: chapter because that made intuitive sense to me when I was reading it.

00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:01.480
[Amit Varma]: That's fine.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:05.160
[Amit Varma]: And your first chapter was called The Evolution of the Universe.

00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:08.240
[Amit Varma]: And there's a very interesting concept in there called skyhooks.

00:08:08.240 --> 00:08:11.360
[Guest]: Can you explain what that's about?

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:17.200
[Guest]: This is a phrase that Daniel Dennett first brought into the conversation, although it

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:23.280
[Guest]: was actually invented by a pilot in World War I who was told to stay up there till we

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:24.280
[Guest]: need you.

00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:27.040
[Guest]: And he replied, this machine is not fitted with skyhooks.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:31.040
[Guest]: I can't attach myself to the sky.

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:35.200
[Guest]: And obviously, you can't build a building with a skyhook, which is a pity because it

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:39.440
[Guest]: would be a nice way to build a building if you could hook a device to the sky and start

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:42.480
[Guest]: from the top.

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:48.520
[Guest]: But that concept, which Daniel Dennett talks about, is a metaphor for the way we talk about

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:53.800
[Guest]: human society all too often and the way we talk about the natural world as well when

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:54.800
[Guest]: we're talking.

00:08:54.800 --> 00:09:01.320
[Guest]: So skyhook is really just a euphemism for God, if you like, in the natural world.

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:08.480
[Guest]: But it's often a euphemism for government in the man-made world.

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:14.880
[Guest]: But in this chapter on the evolution of the universe, I'm really talking about the way

00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:22.000
[Guest]: it dawns on Isaac Newton and other people that God doesn't need to be moving the planets

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:23.380
[Guest]: directly.

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:27.680
[Guest]: They could be moving under their own force.

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:33.920
[Guest]: The pattern and structure of the universe could have come about completely spontaneously

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:36.840
[Guest]: without intervention by a higher power.

00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:40.800
[Guest]: And that was obviously an idea that started to take root in the 17th century and gradually

00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:44.320
[Guest]: developed and that in many ways was resisted.

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:51.320
[Guest]: Newton himself conceded that you don't need God to explain the movement of the planets

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:53.400
[Guest]: today, but something must have started it.

00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:55.160
[Amit Varma]: So perhaps that was God.

00:09:55.160 --> 00:09:59.320
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting you talk about this notion starting in the 17th century, but you

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:04.680
[Amit Varma]: also write a bit about the 5th century BC Roman philosopher Lucretius, who in a sense

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:10.640
[Amit Varma]: anticipated both natural selection and spontaneous order, both Darwin and Adam Smith, in a manner

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:11.640
[Amit Varma]: of speaking.

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:15.560
[Guest]: Yes, Lucretius is a really interesting character.

00:10:15.560 --> 00:10:17.040
[Guest]: We know very little about him.

00:10:17.040 --> 00:10:19.140
[Guest]: We have this one poem that he wrote.

00:10:19.140 --> 00:10:25.680
[Guest]: It was rediscovered in the 1400s after being lost for a century, even though people had

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:27.240
[Guest]: referred to it.

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:30.920
[Guest]: And when it was rediscovered and examined, it was found to be unbelievably modern in

00:10:30.920 --> 00:10:36.560
[Guest]: its way of looking at the world, and it was heavily influential on philosophers like Spinoza

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:41.920
[Guest]: and people like Thomas Jefferson had five copies of it in his library.

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:45.960
[Guest]: Very important part of the Enlightenment was the influence of this one poem by Lucretius.

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:53.240
[Guest]: And Lucretius himself was harking back to Democritus and Epicurus, yes, thank you, that

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:57.160
[Guest]: was the name I was looking for.

00:10:57.160 --> 00:11:00.040
[Guest]: And it's a poem, so we mustn't get too carried away.

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:06.760
[Guest]: He doesn't give details, diagrams, or references for his ideas, but he keeps saying things

00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:10.960
[Guest]: like, look, are you sure you need a god to explain this?

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:14.640
[Guest]: Don't you think actually there's a way in which it could have happened spontaneously?

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:20.120
[Guest]: And he comes agonizingly close to describing the process of natural selection, if you interpret

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:21.840
[Guest]: it generously.

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:27.400
[Guest]: And again and again, he has this refreshing way of saying, look, actually, you can think

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:28.640
[Guest]: about this in a bottom-up way.

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:31.400
[Guest]: You can think about it coming from below.

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:37.680
[Guest]: And it's tempting to think that we were on the brink of a major intellectual breakthrough

00:11:37.680 --> 00:11:40.880
[Guest]: in the first century AD.

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:47.560
[Guest]: Lucretius roughly lived at the same time as Cicero and Caesar and people like that.

00:11:47.560 --> 00:11:51.880
[Guest]: And then something comes along, and we turn our back on this way of looking at the world

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:57.680
[Guest]: for a very long time, and we have to rediscover it in the Enlightenment in the 16th, 17th

00:11:57.680 --> 00:11:58.680
[Amit Varma]: century.

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:03.160
[Amit Varma]: And Lucretius was practically branded as a heretic, and his work was lost and forgotten,

00:12:03.160 --> 00:12:08.240
[Amit Varma]: and possibly because he challenged those top-down notions that the elite sort of had.

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:12.240
[Amit Varma]: And that's the same process that anyone who challenged those notions went through.

00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:16.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, Newton faced it, Darwin faced it, Adam Smith himself faced it.

00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:17.320
[Guest]: That's correct.

00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:20.480
[Guest]: And this is one of the fascinating things, is that it is the ultimate heresy to go around

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:23.240
[Guest]: saying, actually, we don't need God.

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:25.040
[Guest]: We maybe don't need government.

00:12:25.040 --> 00:12:29.760
[Guest]: And as you say, I mean, Lucretius was suppressed, actively and violently suppressed, I mean,

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:36.400
[Guest]: not himself, but his works were, by the Christian church when it took over the Western world.

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:42.960
[Guest]: And fast forward to Adam Smith, a lot of what he says gets him into real trouble and gets

00:12:42.960 --> 00:12:45.280
[Guest]: his followers into real trouble.

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:48.880
[Guest]: People are prosecuted for saying the kinds of things that he's saying.

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:54.240
[Guest]: And my feeling about Adam Smith is that if you look at what he's saying, both in the

00:12:54.240 --> 00:13:01.240
[Guest]: theory of moral sentiments and in The Wealth of Nations, is that he's giving a sort of

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:06.280
[Guest]: general theory of evolution, while Charles Darwin is giving a special theory of evolution,

00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:11.160
[Guest]: by analogy with the special theory of relativity and Einstein, a century before Darwin.

00:13:11.160 --> 00:13:16.040
[Guest]: So the theory of moral sentiments comes out in 1759, Charles Darwin's Origin of Species

00:13:16.040 --> 00:13:18.040
[Guest]: comes out in 1859.

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:26.400
[Guest]: And so Smith is saying society evolves, society emerges, and he's talking about a morality,

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:31.600
[Guest]: how morality emerges, how ethics emerge in the theory of moral sentiments.

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:35.480
[Guest]: And he's doing so very much with the view of it coming about through the interactions

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:39.520
[Guest]: of ordinary people, how you calibrate what is moral and what is not through the reaction

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:41.480
[Guest]: of people in your society.

00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:44.920
[Guest]: And we don't actually need priests to tell us to behave well.

00:13:44.920 --> 00:13:51.880
[Guest]: We work it out ourselves, more or less, depending on how well society is constructed by people's

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:52.880
[Amit Varma]: interactions.

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:55.080
[Amit Varma]: In fact, your second chapter is called The Evolution of Morality.

00:13:55.080 --> 00:13:59.560
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I learned in that chapter is that famous phrase, a metaphor of the invisible

00:13:59.560 --> 00:14:05.840
[Amit Varma]: hand, was not used by Smith in The Wealth of Nations, but before that, in a theory of

00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:10.520
[Amit Varma]: moral sentiments, where he was talking about how morality emerged in a bottom up way, exactly

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:15.000
[Amit Varma]: as you're saying, and that, you know, moral strictures are not dictated by gods on high

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.760
[Amit Varma]: or priests or whatever.

00:14:16.760 --> 00:14:20.560
[Amit Varma]: But they emerge through human interaction, as we learn how to get along with each other

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:22.560
[Guest]: on society in a manner of speaking.

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:23.560
[Guest]: Yes.

00:14:23.560 --> 00:14:27.440
[Guest]: And so it's worth remembering that people think of the invisible hand as purely an economic

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:30.480
[Guest]: idea, but actually, I don't think it was, I think he was.

00:14:30.480 --> 00:14:38.080
[Guest]: It's a delightful phrase, and it's teasing and it sort of hints at this idea that morality

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:39.080
[Guest]: emerges.

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:40.080
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:45.240
[Amit Varma]: So you gave an example of morality emerging, for example, where you contrast the disapproval

00:14:45.240 --> 00:14:49.240
[Amit Varma]: of homosexuality with the disapproval of paedophilia.

00:14:49.240 --> 00:14:54.840
[Amit Varma]: And how one that is a disapproval of homosexuality has sort of receded in the past decades.

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:59.880
[Amit Varma]: And the other has sort of, you know, more people disapprove of paedophilia, for example.

00:14:59.880 --> 00:15:00.880
[Guest]: So if you know,

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:07.440
[Guest]: Very striking, I think, in my lifetime, that, I mean, paedophilia was not condoned, but

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:10.960
[Guest]: it was, you know, there was very little fuss about it.

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:15.360
[Guest]: There were a lot of schoolteachers who were probably behaving badly in the 1950s.

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:19.120
[Guest]: And, you know, they weren't prosecuted, they were just, well, you know, get out the way

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:20.120
[Guest]: or something.

00:15:20.120 --> 00:15:24.520
[Guest]: Whereas homosexuality was illegal at the time, and people were prosecuted.

00:15:24.520 --> 00:15:28.920
[Guest]: People like Alan Turing, you know, committed suicide under pressure from this.

00:15:28.920 --> 00:15:38.360
[Guest]: Today, quite rightly, we are extremely tolerant in society, generally, of people being gay.

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:40.360
[Guest]: And we say, well, that's completely up to them.

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:44.040
[Guest]: That's, you know, that's none of government's business.

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:49.720
[Guest]: But we've become extremely intolerant of people raping or seducing children.

00:15:49.720 --> 00:15:51.360
[Guest]: And again, rightly so.

00:15:51.360 --> 00:15:56.200
[Guest]: But my point is that those changes didn't come about because somebody in charge said,

00:15:56.200 --> 00:16:02.240
[Guest]: look, we're being too lenient about paedophilia and too strict about homosexuality.

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:10.920
[Guest]: They came about because ordinary people changed the conversation themselves.

00:16:10.920 --> 00:16:13.340
[Guest]: Politicians followed suit in these cases, you know.

00:16:13.340 --> 00:16:17.200
[Guest]: Politicians were catching up with the way society was changing its mind about these

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:18.200
[Guest]: things.

00:16:18.200 --> 00:16:22.080
[Guest]: And I think that's a very important lesson in how morality changes.

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:26.200
[Guest]: It tends not to be because some leader tells us what to do.

00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:30.400
[Guest]: This word leadership that everybody uses about how we are going to come on to leadership,

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:31.400
[Guest]: I think.

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:32.400
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:33.640
[Amit Varma]: It is a great mistake.

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:34.640
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:37.440
[Amit Varma]: And I was particularly struck by one paragraph in that chapter, and I'm just going to read

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:38.440
[Amit Varma]: it out again.

00:16:38.440 --> 00:16:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Quote, a Smithian child, you mean Adam Smithian child, a Smithian child developing his sense

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:48.320
[Amit Varma]: of morality in a violent medieval society in Prussia, say, by trial and error, would

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:53.080
[Amit Varma]: end up with a moral code quite different from such a child growing up in a peaceful German

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:54.400
[Amit Varma]: suburb today.

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:58.880
[Amit Varma]: The medieval person would be judged moral if he killed people in defense of his honor

00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:04.200
[Amit Varma]: or his city, whereas today he would be thought moral if he refused meat and gave copiously

00:17:04.200 --> 00:17:08.760
[Amit Varma]: to charity and thought shockingly immoral if he killed somebody for any reason at all,

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:11.920
[Guest]: and especially for honor, stop quote.

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:12.920
[Guest]: Isn't that interesting?

00:17:12.920 --> 00:17:13.920
[Guest]: I know.

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:19.280
[Guest]: This is the Norbert Elias theory of how culture has changed, which Steven Pinker also writes

00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:21.480
[Guest]: about it at great length.

00:17:21.480 --> 00:17:28.440
[Guest]: And what was virtuous in the Middle Ages, it was often to kill bad people, whereas today

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:33.280
[Guest]: it's virtuous not to kill people at all, except possibly in self defense.

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:38.800
[Amit Varma]: In fact, recently, I saw this meme on the internet about some 1920s advertisement, which

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:44.000
[Amit Varma]: told women how they should be the ideal wife, and you and you kind of read all of that,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:45.000
[Amit Varma]: and it's completely shocking.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:49.200
[Amit Varma]: And thankfully, social morals have sort of evolved away from that and changed completely.

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:52.240
[Amit Varma]: But would you say that morality always evolves in the right directions?

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:55.620
[Amit Varma]: I mean, of course, we're defining right from our vantage point.

00:17:55.620 --> 00:17:57.080
[Guest]: But isn't that interesting?

00:17:57.080 --> 00:17:59.440
[Guest]: Why should it evolve in the right direction rather than the wrong direction?

00:17:59.440 --> 00:18:03.040
[Guest]: We've lived through a couple of hundred years in which morality has tended to evolve towards

00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:10.240
[Guest]: liberalism, towards tolerance, towards being less judgmental, except in cases like pedophilia.

00:18:10.240 --> 00:18:14.000
[Guest]: And to some extent, that must be arbitrary.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:19.080
[Guest]: I mean, it must be possible for morality to evolve in the other direction.

00:18:19.080 --> 00:18:24.400
[Guest]: And maybe you see that in some of the more theocratic societies today that Islam has

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:32.160
[Guest]: gone from on the whole being perfectly tolerant to somewhat less tolerant moral code in some

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:39.480
[Guest]: countries towards various forms of blasphemy, homosexuality being an example in that case.

00:18:39.480 --> 00:18:46.640
[Guest]: So fundamentalism does emerge by the same process.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:49.620
[Guest]: And intolerance can emerge by the same process.

00:18:49.620 --> 00:18:55.360
[Guest]: And some of the things we're seeing today on how intolerant people are of free speech,

00:18:55.360 --> 00:18:58.020
[Guest]: etc., could be seen in that light.

00:18:58.020 --> 00:19:02.680
[Guest]: So I think we can take it for granted that morality will continue to evolve in a generally

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:03.680
[Amit Varma]: liberal direction.

00:19:03.680 --> 00:19:04.680
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:09.480
[Amit Varma]: Moving on to sort of your third chapter, which is the evolution of life.

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:14.800
[Amit Varma]: And again, one hardly sort of I think most reasonable people are now except natural selection.

00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:18.640
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing here is that you talk about how Darwin was inspired by the

00:19:18.640 --> 00:19:24.000
[Amit Varma]: ideas of Locke and Smith, and before them, obviously, from Lucretius.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:28.160
[Amit Varma]: And the great quote, which you referred to earlier in this episode is, quote, the general

00:19:28.160 --> 00:19:34.520
[Amit Varma]: theory of evolution came before the special theory, stop quote, when Darwin sort of got

00:19:34.520 --> 00:19:38.880
[Amit Varma]: his ideas, were they kind of heretic or were they an idea whose time had come?

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:43.400
[Guest]: I think if Darwin hadn't come up with a theory of natural selection, we'd still have got

00:19:43.400 --> 00:19:44.400
[Guest]: it around the same time.

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:48.720
[Guest]: I mean, we know that's to be the case because of Alfred Russel Wallace, obviously, who simultaneously

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:50.280
[Guest]: stumbled upon the same idea.

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:56.160
[Guest]: Now, Wallace wasn't going to have quite such a good catalogue of anecdotes and evidence

00:19:56.160 --> 00:20:00.880
[Guest]: to buttress it and quite such good connections as Darwin to push the ideas that might have

00:20:00.880 --> 00:20:03.720
[Guest]: struggled more, it might have come forward in different forms.

00:20:03.720 --> 00:20:08.400
[Guest]: And Darwin was remarkably intellectually consistent in a way that Wallace wasn't, you know, Wallace

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:11.600
[Guest]: refused to believe the human brain could have come about through natural selection, for

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:12.840
[Guest]: example.

00:20:12.840 --> 00:20:17.540
[Guest]: So it would have been different if Darwin hadn't been there to do it.

00:20:17.540 --> 00:20:21.760
[Guest]: But I think you're right in the sense that evolution by natural selection was ripe to

00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:24.700
[Guest]: appear around that period.

00:20:24.700 --> 00:20:27.880
[Guest]: We had the pieces in place.

00:20:27.880 --> 00:20:35.160
[Guest]: And as I say, to a surprising extent, it comes from these Enlightenment thinkers from the

00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:40.480
[Guest]: 18th century, people like Locke and Smith and so on, influencing people like Darwin.

00:20:40.480 --> 00:20:48.100
[Guest]: The milieu that he grew up in was very much based around these ideas of Smith and people

00:20:48.100 --> 00:20:52.080
[Guest]: like that about free markets, about freedom generally.

00:20:52.080 --> 00:20:57.760
[Guest]: And I think, you know, you needed to plow the ground before you could sow the seeds

00:20:57.760 --> 00:20:59.800
[Guest]: of Darwinism.

00:20:59.800 --> 00:21:00.960
[Guest]: But it was still very heretical.

00:21:00.960 --> 00:21:06.080
[Guest]: I mean, it was still hugely resisted, mainly from the point of view of religion, which

00:21:06.080 --> 00:21:07.760
[Guest]: it was seen as a threat to.

00:21:07.760 --> 00:21:12.560
[Guest]: And of course, still is, I mean, in many parts of the world, particularly parts of America,

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:17.160
[Guest]: natural selection is rejected out of hand, because it seems to contradict the Bible.

00:21:17.160 --> 00:21:22.600
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's very sort of interesting that before Darwin, all the thinkers who sort of

00:21:22.600 --> 00:21:25.960
[Amit Varma]: expressed such ideas, you know, God was a thing you couldn't touch.

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:30.720
[Amit Varma]: So even Newton, when he would say things which would normally lead you to atheistic conclusions,

00:21:30.720 --> 00:21:36.940
[Amit Varma]: or even Descartes, would, you know, the hedge at the very end, and sort of pay lip service

00:21:36.940 --> 00:21:40.440
[Amit Varma]: to theistic concepts, at the end of the day.

00:21:40.440 --> 00:21:45.480
[Guest]: Well, Amit, I'm curious as to what, to the extent to which I'm seeing everything through

00:21:45.480 --> 00:21:50.200
[Guest]: the lens of Christianity, whereas, of course, there are many, you know, there's always been

00:21:50.200 --> 00:21:55.160
[Guest]: many people living under different religious dispositions.

00:21:55.160 --> 00:21:59.720
[Guest]: And I'm curious as to how easy or difficult it would be under Hinduism or under Buddhism

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:05.360
[Guest]: or under Islam, for these bottom up ideas to emerge.

00:22:05.360 --> 00:22:06.680
[Guest]: And of course, they must have done.

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:13.440
[Guest]: And sometimes unsuccessfully and been suppressed, and sometimes come through more successfully.

00:22:13.440 --> 00:22:20.700
[Guest]: It sort of feels like the Buddhists should have been quickest to this, because in a way,

00:22:20.700 --> 00:22:25.560
[Guest]: the deity in Buddhism is a bit of a bottom up deity, if I could put it that way.

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:28.420
[Guest]: I don't know what you think about that.

00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:29.420
[Amit Varma]: It's interesting.

00:22:29.420 --> 00:22:33.480
[Amit Varma]: And also, I think, Hinduism is evolving in more intolerant directions today, there's

00:22:33.480 --> 00:22:37.680
[Amit Varma]: a tradition within Hinduism that talks about that is an atheist tradition, the Charvaka

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:39.880
[Amit Varma]: tradition and so on.

00:22:39.880 --> 00:22:45.120
[Amit Varma]: Having said that, most of the Enlightenment ideas, to be quite frank, came from the West.

00:22:45.120 --> 00:22:49.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, a friend of mine was attempting to write a book on the history of liberalism

00:22:49.720 --> 00:22:54.920
[Amit Varma]: in India and actually trying to examine whether there are sort of liberal ideas that took

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:58.960
[Amit Varma]: root in India spontaneously, and it's very hard to come across them, they're all sort

00:22:58.960 --> 00:23:04.600
[Amit Varma]: of guided by God or other sort of top down ways.

00:23:04.600 --> 00:23:08.720
[Amit Varma]: So you know, all of these ideas of spontaneous order and natural selection have definitely

00:23:08.720 --> 00:23:12.440
[Amit Varma]: come to us now from the West, but I think all the world is one now.

00:23:12.440 --> 00:23:15.120
[Amit Varma]: So it's sort of kind of moot.

00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:18.240
[Amit Varma]: Your fourth chapter was very interesting, especially because the first book I read of

00:23:18.240 --> 00:23:24.240
[Amit Varma]: yours was Genome, all those years ago, and your fourth chapter is about the evolution

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:31.040
[Amit Varma]: of genes, and where you talk about how most people, even scientists tend to think of genes

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:35.920
[Amit Varma]: in terms of a skyhook, that genes are the master plan for the body, but you say it's

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:36.920
[Guest]: not so.

00:23:36.920 --> 00:23:43.720
[Guest]: Yes, this is an interesting one, I think, because when we first decoded the human genome,

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:49.680
[Guest]: there's a lot of literature out there in genetics talking about wanting to find the master genes,

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:54.720
[Guest]: the genes that control the other genes, and so on, and this is just the wrong way of looking

00:23:54.720 --> 00:23:55.720
[Guest]: at it.

00:23:55.720 --> 00:23:58.180
[Guest]: This is a network, not a hierarchy.

00:23:58.180 --> 00:24:02.440
[Guest]: Every gene is affecting every other gene, and so on, not every gene, but most genes

00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:05.400
[Guest]: are affecting other genes in different ways.

00:24:05.400 --> 00:24:11.400
[Guest]: And we had to get used to the idea that there were only 21,000 and not more genes, and that

00:24:11.400 --> 00:24:15.760
[Guest]: while there are genes that switch on earlier in life, or whatever, and start a cascade

00:24:15.760 --> 00:24:24.300
[Guest]: of events that result in other things, most genes are contributing proteins that are parts

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:31.720
[Guest]: of a machine, rather than chains in a series of events, and I think that is an idea that

00:24:31.720 --> 00:24:32.720
[Guest]: hasn't quite sunk in.

00:24:32.720 --> 00:24:42.400
[Guest]: So even geneticists confronted with this extremely bottom-up system, which is the development

00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:49.800
[Guest]: of an incredibly complex body from 10-20,000 genes, have tended to think in terms of leadership

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:53.400
[Guest]: by certain genes over other genes.

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:57.640
[Amit Varma]: And your point is that every gene, if you use a metaphor of acting, because genes don't

00:24:57.640 --> 00:25:01.720
[Amit Varma]: actually have volition, but every gene, in a sense, is acting in its own self interest.

00:25:01.720 --> 00:25:04.840
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't really give a damn about the master plan.

00:25:04.840 --> 00:25:09.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, in the same way as you spoke about feeding lunch to the city of Bombay, and here

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:13.880
[Amit Varma]: I am in the city of Bombay, and I'm just doing my own thing, but I am, in a sense, contributing

00:25:13.880 --> 00:25:18.080
[Amit Varma]: to this master plan of giving lunch to all of Bombay, including to myself.

00:25:18.080 --> 00:25:22.480
[Amit Varma]: But it's not a conscious directed way, it's sort of, I just do what I do, everybody does

00:25:22.480 --> 00:25:24.520
[Amit Varma]: what they does, and the city runs as it does.

00:25:24.520 --> 00:25:29.360
[Guest]: Yeah, and I think that's, it's a very good analogy, a cell is like a city.

00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:33.200
[Guest]: You know, there's lots of individuals do going about their business doing their different

00:25:33.200 --> 00:25:34.200
[Guest]: things.

00:25:34.200 --> 00:25:39.280
[Guest]: And for the city to function, all it needs is for everybody to do their bit, not to try

00:25:39.280 --> 00:25:41.080
[Amit Varma]: and tell everyone else what to do.

00:25:41.080 --> 00:25:46.500
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sort of struck by another quote of yours, which, again, harks back to Dawkins

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:52.200
[Amit Varma]: in his classic book, quote, it is a selfishness of the genes that enables individuals to be

00:25:52.200 --> 00:25:53.200
[Amit Varma]: selfless.

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:54.560
[Guest]: Stop quote.

00:25:54.560 --> 00:25:59.480
[Guest]: Well, Richard Dawkins wrote The Selfish Gene in the 1970s, very influential on me, I read

00:25:59.480 --> 00:26:05.240
[Guest]: it when I was just starting at university, and he then was one of my teachers.

00:26:05.240 --> 00:26:12.720
[Guest]: And I think he had a blinding insight that the generous behavior that human beings show

00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:18.100
[Guest]: could come about because of the self interest of genes rather than because of genes for

00:26:18.100 --> 00:26:20.280
[Guest]: generosity sort of thing.

00:26:20.280 --> 00:26:23.360
[Guest]: And it's, you know, it's quite a hard concept to get your head around.

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:28.960
[Guest]: And you know, how could we be anything other than the results of replicating devices trying

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:32.520
[Guest]: to ensure their progression into the next generation.

00:26:32.520 --> 00:26:35.880
[Guest]: And that is, when you think about it, a very Smithian concept.

00:26:35.880 --> 00:26:42.120
[Guest]: Now, a lot of biologists, evolutionary biologists are convinced by this kind of selfish gene

00:26:42.120 --> 00:26:47.240
[Guest]: argument would not find themselves at the free market end of the economic or political

00:26:47.240 --> 00:26:52.440
[Guest]: spectrum and probably haven't understood that parallel, in my view.

00:26:52.440 --> 00:26:54.680
[Amit Varma]: And that's a pretty stunning dissonance.

00:26:54.680 --> 00:26:58.400
[Amit Varma]: You sort of end the chapter by saying, quote, the more we understand genomics, the more

00:26:58.400 --> 00:27:03.640
[Amit Varma]: it confirms evolution, stop quote, moving on now to your fifth chapter, which is the

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:05.800
[Amit Varma]: evolution of culture.

00:27:05.800 --> 00:27:12.240
[Amit Varma]: And again, I'm going to quote a para from the start quote, one of the great intellectual

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:16.920
[Amit Varma]: breakthroughs of recent decades led by two evolutionary theorists named Rob Boyd and

00:27:16.920 --> 00:27:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Pete Richardson, is the realization that Darwin's mechanism of selective survival resulted in

00:27:22.960 --> 00:27:27.880
[Amit Varma]: cumulative complexity applies to human culture in all its aspects to I think I read that

00:27:27.880 --> 00:27:28.880
[Amit Varma]: somewhere.

00:27:28.880 --> 00:27:34.080
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, our habits and our institutions, from language to cities are constantly changing.

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And the mechanism of change turns out to be surprisingly Darwinian.

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:44.680
[Amit Varma]: It is gradual, undirected, mutational, inexorable, combinatorial, selective, and in some weak

00:27:44.680 --> 00:27:51.200
[Amit Varma]: sense, progressive, stop quote, and an illustration you give of how culture evolves is language.

00:27:51.200 --> 00:27:57.080
[Guest]: Yeah, I think language is a very good case to think because we can see language changing

00:27:57.080 --> 00:27:58.080
[Guest]: before our eyes.

00:27:58.080 --> 00:28:02.760
[Guest]: We see pronunciation changing, we see vocabulary changing, we see new words, we see words changing

00:28:02.760 --> 00:28:04.280
[Guest]: their meanings and so on.

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:08.840
[Guest]: And we know, don't we, that no one is trying to do this.

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:13.520
[Guest]: No one is setting out deliberately to introduce a new word into the English language or something

00:28:13.520 --> 00:28:14.840
[Guest]: like that.

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:19.460
[Guest]: It's coming about very gradually by mutation and selection, by relatively random changes,

00:28:19.460 --> 00:28:22.680
[Guest]: some of which are accepted and some of which are rejected.

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:27.840
[Guest]: And one of the things that people used to say is, well, hang on, culture cannot be Darwinian

00:28:27.840 --> 00:28:30.480
[Guest]: because a lot of the things we do are deliberate.

00:28:30.480 --> 00:28:36.040
[Guest]: We are conscious, we're planning things, we're trying to change something.

00:28:36.040 --> 00:28:38.320
[Guest]: That makes it very, you know, that's directed mutation.

00:28:38.320 --> 00:28:42.600
[Guest]: The point of natural selection is that it has to be random mutation in order to discover

00:28:42.600 --> 00:28:44.400
[Guest]: new things.

00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:49.360
[Guest]: But actually, there's been some good mathematical modeling that shows that while even if most

00:28:49.360 --> 00:28:53.680
[Guest]: of the things people try and do are conscious and are deliberate, as long as there's an

00:28:53.680 --> 00:28:57.600
[Guest]: element of randomness, as long as there's an element of trial and error in there, you

00:28:57.600 --> 00:29:01.880
[Guest]: will get a surprisingly powerful Darwinian evolution happening.

00:29:01.880 --> 00:29:06.960
[Guest]: And Joe Henrich and his colleagues particularly have made this argument that actually, and

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:13.120
[Guest]: once you drill down into human culture and understand how it works, it looks much more

00:29:13.120 --> 00:29:19.680
[Guest]: evolutionary and much less led and planned than we have tended to assume.

00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:24.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of the points you make is that language is learned, not taught.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.760
[Amit Varma]: And an example you give of this is top down language teaching versus bottom up language

00:29:28.760 --> 00:29:33.760
[Amit Varma]: teaching and top down would be like, say, if I at the age of 44, try to learn a foreign

00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:38.960
[Amit Varma]: language like French is for me, and, you know, I really struggled, I, you know, start learning

00:29:38.960 --> 00:29:41.840
[Amit Varma]: it in a superficial way, and it could be really hard going.

00:29:41.840 --> 00:29:50.840
[Amit Varma]: But every baby born in France just does it so naturally in the bottom up kind of way.

00:29:50.840 --> 00:29:51.840
[Guest]: That's right.

00:29:51.840 --> 00:29:55.580
[Guest]: And, you know, I think we've made a mistake in trying, I mean, I was taught Latin and

00:29:55.580 --> 00:30:02.280
[Guest]: Greek when I was a child, I remember almost none of it now, it's faded.

00:30:02.280 --> 00:30:08.120
[Guest]: And learning from being taught those kind of languages is surprisingly difficult, whereas

00:30:08.120 --> 00:30:13.600
[Guest]: if I had lived in France or Germany or India, I would have, as a child, I would have very

00:30:13.600 --> 00:30:14.600
[Guest]: quickly absorbed.

00:30:14.600 --> 00:30:20.040
[Guest]: And, you know, I did pick up, I mean, I lived in India for a few months, one year, and I

00:30:20.040 --> 00:30:23.800
[Guest]: didn't become proficient in Hindi, but, you know, I absorbed it without anybody teaching

00:30:23.800 --> 00:30:24.800
[Guest]: me.

00:30:24.800 --> 00:30:26.920
[Guest]: Now, of course, it helps to have a language teacher.

00:30:26.920 --> 00:30:30.980
[Guest]: But essentially, what a language teacher is, is just, you know, a good one, it's just immersing

00:30:30.980 --> 00:30:33.960
[Guest]: you in the experience so you can do the learning.

00:30:33.960 --> 00:30:37.120
[Guest]: And I think that's a good example of how we learn rather than teach.

00:30:37.120 --> 00:30:42.880
[Amit Varma]: And I found that you also outlined a number of rules on how sort of language tends to

00:30:42.880 --> 00:30:43.880
[Amit Varma]: evolve.

00:30:43.880 --> 00:30:48.560
[Amit Varma]: For example, frequently used words tend to be short, common words change slowly.

00:30:48.560 --> 00:30:52.160
[Amit Varma]: For example, the meaning of the you said is never really going to change because, you

00:30:52.160 --> 00:30:55.760
[Amit Varma]: know, you'd have to make too many people learn a new meaning.

00:30:55.760 --> 00:30:58.680
[Amit Varma]: But something like prevaricate has, in fact, changed.

00:30:58.680 --> 00:30:59.760
[Guest]: Yes, exactly.

00:30:59.760 --> 00:31:04.080
[Guest]: So the word prevaricate is now routinely used, certainly in the UK, I don't know about elsewhere

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:06.580
[Guest]: in the world, to mean delay.

00:31:06.580 --> 00:31:07.580
[Guest]: It doesn't mean that.

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:09.500
[Guest]: It means to lie, actually.

00:31:09.500 --> 00:31:12.240
[Guest]: People when they say prevaricate, they're thinking of procrastinate.

00:31:12.240 --> 00:31:15.880
[Guest]: But they actually, for some reason, they use the word prevaricate instead.

00:31:15.880 --> 00:31:19.680
[Guest]: That's changed in my lifetime, there's no point getting cross about it and saying we've

00:31:19.680 --> 00:31:23.580
[Guest]: lost a perfectly good word, procrastinate, and we've, you know, we've lost the meaning

00:31:23.580 --> 00:31:26.240
[Guest]: of the word prevaricate.

00:31:26.240 --> 00:31:27.560
[Guest]: These things happen.

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:33.000
[Guest]: But it's not going to happen to a small word like me or and or the, you know, those don't

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:34.000
[Guest]: change.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:39.520
[Guest]: Those regularities, those rules look like they were, you know, set down by some Supreme

00:31:39.520 --> 00:31:42.560
[Guest]: Court of the English language, which, of course, is not the case.

00:31:42.560 --> 00:31:45.640
[Amit Varma]: It's that it's a natural pragmatism of all of us.

00:31:45.640 --> 00:31:48.360
[Amit Varma]: It's natural pragmatism is a very good way of putting it.

00:31:48.360 --> 00:31:52.320
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, before we started recording this podcast, I told you, I'll record the intro

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:53.320
[Amit Varma]: and the outro later.

00:31:53.320 --> 00:31:58.040
[Amit Varma]: And then it strikes me that outro also in a manner of speaking is a word that is evolving.

00:31:58.040 --> 00:32:00.920
[Amit Varma]: Because there's really no such word as outro.

00:32:00.920 --> 00:32:05.720
[Amit Varma]: But well, I would argue now there is because people use it that it's everyone understands

00:32:05.720 --> 00:32:07.120
[Amit Varma]: what one means by it.

00:32:07.120 --> 00:32:08.440
[Guest]: Well, who invented it?

00:32:08.440 --> 00:32:09.440
[Guest]: When?

00:32:09.440 --> 00:32:10.440
[Amit Varma]: Who started the word outro?

00:32:10.440 --> 00:32:15.000
