00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:45.120
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the Unseen.

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:50.360
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with the author Matt Ridley about the evolution of everything.

00:33:50.360 --> 00:33:53.800
[Amit Varma]: To go back to your fifth chapter about the evolution of culture, there was one sentence

00:33:53.800 --> 00:33:57.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to ask you to explain to me, which I didn't really quite understand, but it's

00:33:57.600 --> 00:34:03.720
[Amit Varma]: very intriguing, which is you write that in people, genes are probably the slaves, not

00:34:03.720 --> 00:34:05.360
[Amit Varma]: the masters of culture.

00:34:05.360 --> 00:34:06.360
[Guest]: Ah, yes.

00:34:06.360 --> 00:34:13.440
[Guest]: Well, what I think I'm trying to argue here is that gene culture coevolution is the idea

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:20.000
[Guest]: that if culture changes, that could put pressure on the genes to change.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:30.600
[Guest]: So for example, we have tended to argue that in order to become modern linguistic people,

00:34:30.600 --> 00:34:32.280
[Guest]: something had to change in our brain.

00:34:32.280 --> 00:34:38.240
[Guest]: And after that, we began speaking because at last we had the circuitry to use language

00:34:38.240 --> 00:34:40.180
[Guest]: in our heads.

00:34:40.180 --> 00:34:45.160
[Guest]: I've argued, and I've published peer-reviewed papers arguing this actually, that it could

00:34:45.160 --> 00:34:46.900
[Guest]: be the other way around.

00:34:46.900 --> 00:34:54.880
[Guest]: So for example, if we started using our voices a lot to communicate, that would put selective

00:34:54.880 --> 00:35:00.680
[Guest]: pressure on whoever could articulate particularly well to have more children because they're

00:35:00.680 --> 00:35:02.240
[Guest]: better at communicating.

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:07.120
[Guest]: So it's the culture that starts the change and the genes that follow.

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:10.880
[Guest]: The culture is the horse and genes are the cart.

00:35:10.880 --> 00:35:13.320
[Amit Varma]: And it's like the virtuous cycle in that case.

00:35:13.320 --> 00:35:16.320
[Guest]: Yes, that's true, exactly.

00:35:16.320 --> 00:35:17.680
[Guest]: It's a virtuous circle.

00:35:17.680 --> 00:35:20.120
[Guest]: But we have very nice examples of this.

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:29.240
[Guest]: For example, in tolerance of milk, the ability to digest milk, which is something that Western

00:35:29.240 --> 00:35:36.960
[Guest]: Europeans have and some Africans have, but is relatively rare elsewhere in the world.

00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:40.560
[Guest]: I think it's relatively common in India, but I'm not sure.

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:43.760
[Guest]: But in the Far East, it's really quite scarce.

00:35:43.760 --> 00:35:44.760
[Guest]: Now why is that?

00:35:44.760 --> 00:35:49.720
[Guest]: We're talking about adults, I mean obviously children can digest milk.

00:35:49.720 --> 00:35:51.120
[Guest]: Lactose is the key thing.

00:35:51.120 --> 00:35:56.400
[Guest]: Lactose is a sugar-founded milk that adult human generally can't digest unless they come

00:35:56.400 --> 00:35:58.440
[Guest]: from certain cultures.

00:35:58.440 --> 00:36:00.240
[Guest]: Now what happened?

00:36:00.240 --> 00:36:07.480
[Guest]: Did people say, oh good, I'm lactose tolerant, therefore I'm going to invent dairy farming?

00:36:07.480 --> 00:36:12.600
[Guest]: Or did they invent dairy farming and get some benefit out of eating milk because after it's

00:36:12.600 --> 00:36:16.920
[Guest]: got proteins and other things in it and you could turn it into cheese and eat that, which

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:18.280
[Guest]: is fine.

00:36:18.280 --> 00:36:22.440
[Guest]: But they all had a bit of indigestion from the lactose.

00:36:22.440 --> 00:36:29.760
[Guest]: And then people who genetically found that their infant genes for lactose digestion remained

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:34.600
[Guest]: switched on throughout life were suddenly at an advantage.

00:36:34.600 --> 00:36:37.360
[Guest]: They got more energy out of the milk than other people.

00:36:37.360 --> 00:36:38.800
[Guest]: And so the genes started changing.

00:36:38.800 --> 00:36:43.840
[Guest]: So we know in that case, I mean that's far more plausible as to what happened, is that

00:36:43.840 --> 00:36:48.920
[Guest]: the culture changed towards keeping animals for their milk and that was followed by a

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:49.920
[Guest]: genetic change.

00:36:49.920 --> 00:36:53.920
[Amit Varma]: But with that sort of natural selection not happening now, it's kind of moot, right?

00:36:53.920 --> 00:36:58.560
[Amit Varma]: You can look at the past and talk about culture influencing genes, but that's no longer happening

00:36:58.560 --> 00:36:59.560
[Guest]: obviously, right?

00:36:59.560 --> 00:37:01.560
[Guest]: Well, I'm not so sure.

00:37:01.560 --> 00:37:06.160
[Guest]: I think there are things that are happening today that are bound to be changing, putting

00:37:06.160 --> 00:37:09.000
[Guest]: genetic influences on us.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:10.120
[Guest]: It's hard to think of an example.

00:37:10.120 --> 00:37:14.800
[Guest]: One of the problems with modern culture is it changes so fast and often not consistently

00:37:14.800 --> 00:37:17.640
[Guest]: in the same direction for a long time.

00:37:17.640 --> 00:37:25.240
[Guest]: But suppose there's a lot of people who have relatively small numbers of children today.

00:37:25.240 --> 00:37:30.800
[Guest]: Now if there's some cultural habit that's leading people to be less likely to have babies

00:37:30.800 --> 00:37:37.360
[Guest]: and other cultural habit that's leading people to have lots of babies, then these will change.

00:37:37.360 --> 00:37:41.640
[Amit Varma]: Then we're in trouble because I always argued that smarter people have less babies.

00:37:41.640 --> 00:37:44.320
[Guest]: Well, there is that.

00:37:44.320 --> 00:37:48.880
[Guest]: And actually, if you look at all religions around the world, whether you look at Protestant

00:37:48.880 --> 00:37:56.440
[Guest]: Christianity, Catholic Christianity, different forms of Islam, Judaism, Hinduism, on the

00:37:56.440 --> 00:38:00.840
[Guest]: whole, the more orthodox and fundamentalist people are, the more children they're having.

00:38:00.840 --> 00:38:05.080
[Guest]: There's a very good book called The Religious Shall Inherit the Earth, I think it's called.

00:38:05.080 --> 00:38:10.560
[Guest]: And the argument here is that now that we're limiting family size voluntarily, and it used

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:14.000
[Guest]: to be that everybody tried to have as many children as possible, but now that most people

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:21.320
[Guest]: are settling for one or two children, the exceptions are going to be dominating posterity

00:38:21.320 --> 00:38:22.400
[Guest]: to a surprising extent.

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:24.320
[Guest]: Now those exceptions tend to be fundamentalist.

00:38:24.320 --> 00:38:30.440
[Guest]: So if there is a gene for fundamentalism, like, exactly, it's on, it's on the rise.

00:38:30.440 --> 00:38:34.040
[Amit Varma]: You end that chapter on culture by writing about cities.

00:38:34.040 --> 00:38:37.120
[Amit Varma]: And you point out, you know, in India, these days, our Prime Minister Narendra Modi keeps

00:38:37.120 --> 00:38:42.160
[Amit Varma]: talking about smart cities, he wants to design new cities, and, you know, a huge amount of

00:38:42.160 --> 00:38:43.160
[Amit Varma]: top down thinking.

00:38:43.160 --> 00:38:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And what you actually point out is that most big cities emerge spontaneously, they weren't

00:38:48.120 --> 00:38:51.960
[Amit Varma]: planned by some government or higher power or whatever.

00:38:51.960 --> 00:38:56.320
[Amit Varma]: And an example you give of this is England in the first half of the 19th century.

00:38:56.320 --> 00:38:57.320
[Guest]: Yes.

00:38:57.320 --> 00:39:04.120
[Guest]: No, I mean, the growth of industrial cities like Manchester or Birmingham in the UK is

00:39:04.120 --> 00:39:08.600
[Guest]: an entirely spontaneous phenomenon, there's there's no, you know, government didn't set

00:39:08.600 --> 00:39:12.080
[Guest]: out to say, right, we're going to build some bigger cities.

00:39:12.080 --> 00:39:16.880
[Guest]: It's true that when people realized how cities were growing, they then said, hang on, let's

00:39:16.880 --> 00:39:20.160
[Guest]: plan the infrastructure so that it's more user friendly.

00:39:20.160 --> 00:39:25.160
[Guest]: So for example, the grid system that you get in the middle of many American cities, and

00:39:25.160 --> 00:39:29.800
[Guest]: indeed, curiously, in Glasgow, for example, is an example of top down and, and we're often

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:30.800
[Guest]: very grateful for it.

00:39:30.800 --> 00:39:34.200
[Guest]: I mean, you couldn't get around Manhattan so easily if it was a higgledy piggledy city

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:39.680
[Guest]: like, well, you could, I mean, we get around London, okay, we get around Bombay, okay.

00:39:39.680 --> 00:39:45.840
[Guest]: Obviously, you know, you can't have zero government in a city, you can't have no police, you can't

00:39:45.840 --> 00:39:50.720
[Guest]: have no ability to build the roads, you can't have no traffic lights, you know, that's not

00:39:50.720 --> 00:39:52.600
[Guest]: what we're saying.

00:39:52.600 --> 00:39:58.000
[Guest]: What we're saying is that you do have to take into account that these things will change

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:03.000
[Guest]: spontaneously and you may be wrong if you plan for them to change in one way, and they

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.080
[Guest]: actually want to change in a different way.

00:40:05.080 --> 00:40:10.120
[Guest]: It's a bit like the way if you set up a park, and you put the paths across the park wrong,

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:12.880
[Guest]: and people say, no, actually, I want to work from that corner to that corner, not this

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:17.560
[Guest]: corner to this corner, then people will make what they call desire lines, which is tracks

00:40:17.560 --> 00:40:18.560
[Guest]: across the grass.

00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:22.640
[Guest]: And you're much better moving your concrete to where the tracks are than trying to put

00:40:22.640 --> 00:40:26.440
[Guest]: up big signs saying keep off the grass, stick to these tracks.

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:30.480
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, it's much better, therefore, letting a city or an urban settlement evolve

00:40:30.480 --> 00:40:34.560
[Amit Varma]: as it will, and then building the infrastructure to service it and, you know, getting all of

00:40:34.560 --> 00:40:39.480
[Amit Varma]: that done rather than trying to second guess what people may want and putting that in place.

00:40:39.480 --> 00:40:40.480
[Guest]: Correct.

00:40:40.480 --> 00:40:44.040
[Guest]: And I mean, although, as I say, you can go too far, you do have to anticipate demand

00:40:44.040 --> 00:40:47.920
[Guest]: to some extent, for example, for water or something like that.

00:40:47.920 --> 00:40:52.200
[Guest]: But it's important to be flexible and say, look, hang on, the way people want to live

00:40:52.200 --> 00:40:56.760
[Guest]: in cities these days is actually changing, and we shouldn't disapprove of it, we should

00:40:56.760 --> 00:41:01.200
[Guest]: just change the way we're operating so as to make room for it.

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:04.520
[Amit Varma]: And a magnificent book I'd recommend to my listeners, and I know you must also be a fan

00:41:04.520 --> 00:41:07.880
[Amit Varma]: of it is Death and Life of Great American Cities by Jane Jacobs.

00:41:07.880 --> 00:41:08.880
[Guest]: Oh, yes.

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:13.200
[Guest]: I mean, Jane Jacobs is the genius behind these ideas for cities, because she was the one

00:41:13.200 --> 00:41:21.360
[Guest]: who, who campaigned against the sort of central planning of infrastructure in New York that

00:41:21.360 --> 00:41:22.360
[Guest]: was ruining neighborhoods.

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:23.360
[Amit Varma]: Epitomized by Robert Moses.

00:41:23.360 --> 00:41:24.360
[Amit Varma]: Robert Moses.

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:25.360
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:41:25.360 --> 00:41:26.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:41:26.360 --> 00:41:27.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:41:27.360 --> 00:41:34.240
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on now to chapter six, the evolution of the economy, which begins by your invoking

