[Amit Varma]: Bastia wrote about feeding Paris, where he said that who feeds Paris, that if you have

00:41:48.480 --> 00:41:53.480
[Amit Varma]: a central planner who tries to feed Paris, the task will simply be too overwhelming.

00:41:53.480 --> 00:41:56.480
[Amit Varma]: But hey, Paris manages quite fine on its own.

00:41:56.480 --> 00:41:57.480
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:41:57.480 --> 00:41:58.480
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:41:58.480 --> 00:41:59.480
[Guest]: I think this is a great insight.

00:41:59.480 --> 00:42:03.680
[Guest]: It's a great way of looking at the world and Bastia really nails it here.

00:42:03.680 --> 00:42:07.760
[Guest]: Because with food, people immediately get what you're talking about, I find, that if

00:42:07.760 --> 00:42:16.200
[Guest]: you say, look, there's a better way of feeding Bombay, and that is to put one food commissioner

00:42:16.200 --> 00:42:22.000
[Guest]: in charge of it, and he can plan well in ahead and make sure that the right amount of food

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:23.760
[Guest]: is available to the right kind of people.

00:42:23.760 --> 00:42:25.720
[Guest]: Well, we know that doesn't work.

00:42:25.720 --> 00:42:26.720
[Guest]: It's called central planning.

00:42:26.720 --> 00:42:32.080
[Guest]: It was tried in the Soviet Union and other places, and it's a disaster wherever it's

00:42:32.080 --> 00:42:33.080
[Guest]: tried.

00:42:33.080 --> 00:42:39.200
[Guest]: But we know that the way to achieve the feeding of a city is supply and demand, that if there's

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:45.720
[Guest]: not enough demand for fish and there's too much supply, there's not enough supply of

00:42:45.720 --> 00:42:52.480
[Guest]: bread, and there's too much demand for bread, then the price of fish and bread will reflect

00:42:52.480 --> 00:42:59.520
[Guest]: that, and that will automatically adjust without anyone anticipating it, without anyone ordering

00:42:59.520 --> 00:43:01.480
[Amit Varma]: it, without anyone leading it.

00:43:01.480 --> 00:43:04.840
[Amit Varma]: And there's a nice dystopian novel to be written there, the food commissioner.

00:43:04.840 --> 00:43:06.840
[Guest]: There is, that's a good point.

00:43:06.840 --> 00:43:07.840
[Guest]: Let's do it.

00:43:07.840 --> 00:43:08.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:43:08.840 --> 00:43:13.160
[Amit Varma]: And one interesting point you made, which, you know, and so for a moment, I'll ask you

00:43:13.160 --> 00:43:18.240
[Amit Varma]: to kind of digress, you say here, today, few people appreciate just how similar the arguments

00:43:18.240 --> 00:43:20.400
[Amit Varma]: made by Smith and Darwin are.

00:43:20.400 --> 00:43:24.240
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, essentially, to me, the way I see it, it's an identical argument.

00:43:24.240 --> 00:43:28.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, natural selection is spontaneous order, which is a term people use for the way the

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:32.200
[Amit Varma]: economy sort of forms itself, that you don't need a central planner, that all of these

00:43:32.200 --> 00:43:33.480
[Amit Varma]: things happen by themselves.

00:43:33.480 --> 00:43:38.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's a beautiful, almost mystical process, in a sense, like Douglas Adams once said that

00:43:38.280 --> 00:43:43.360
[Amit Varma]: he didn't need God because the wonder of natural selection was enough to fill him with that

00:43:43.360 --> 00:43:46.040
[Amit Varma]: kind of amazing awe.

00:43:46.040 --> 00:43:52.640
[Amit Varma]: But yet we find that when it comes to politics, you have, you know, people on one side who

00:43:52.640 --> 00:43:56.920
[Amit Varma]: are creationists of one sort, and people on the other side, people on the left are actually

00:43:56.920 --> 00:43:59.360
[Amit Varma]: creationists when it comes to the economy.

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:01.640
[Amit Varma]: Why do you think that is?

00:44:01.640 --> 00:44:03.800
[Guest]: This is a fascinating phenomenon, isn't it?

00:44:03.800 --> 00:44:11.320
[Guest]: So I've, in my career, mixed with free market economists and evolutionary biologists.

00:44:11.320 --> 00:44:15.240
[Guest]: And I've often said to them, you guys are saying the same thing.

00:44:15.240 --> 00:44:16.240
[Guest]: Do you realize it?

00:44:16.240 --> 00:44:21.400
[Guest]: And the evolutionary biologists will all vote for, nearly all, not all, but will mostly

00:44:21.400 --> 00:44:27.080
[Guest]: vote for a sort of socialist view of the economy, and the free market economists will quite

00:44:27.080 --> 00:44:33.120
[Guest]: often be found saying, well, no, I, you know, I don't really think Darwinism's right.

00:44:33.120 --> 00:44:36.280
[Guest]: You know, because they're on the, free market economists tend to be associated with the

00:44:36.280 --> 00:44:41.080
[Guest]: right wing, certainly in the United States, whereas evolutionary biologists tend to be

00:44:41.080 --> 00:44:45.360
[Guest]: on the left wing because they're academics and scientists, and most are.

00:44:45.360 --> 00:44:50.360
[Amit Varma]: And I long to bash heads together and say, hang on, yeah, exactly.

00:44:50.360 --> 00:44:52.800
[Guest]: And you know, forget right and left.

00:44:52.800 --> 00:44:55.840
[Guest]: This idea of spontaneous order is more important than that.

00:44:55.840 --> 00:44:58.040
[Guest]: And it's neither one thing nor the other.

00:44:58.040 --> 00:45:02.200
[Guest]: I mean, it's certainly, you know, if by right wing, you mean authoritarian, it's certainly

00:45:02.200 --> 00:45:03.200
[Guest]: not that.

00:45:03.200 --> 00:45:05.160
[Guest]: It's the very opposite of that.

00:45:05.160 --> 00:45:09.760
[Guest]: And you know, what could be more liberating than the idea that ordinary people are in

00:45:09.760 --> 00:45:14.160
[Guest]: charge of their own destiny through a slightly messy, but rather beautiful system of spontaneous

00:45:14.160 --> 00:45:15.160
[Amit Varma]: order?

00:45:15.160 --> 00:45:17.360
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, that's something where you talk about the economy as well.

00:45:17.360 --> 00:45:22.880
[Amit Varma]: Again, I'll quote from you, quote, free market commerce is the only system of human organization

00:45:22.880 --> 00:45:29.520
[Amit Varma]: yet devised where ordinary people are in charge, unlike feudalism, communism, fascism, slavery,

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:34.320
[Amit Varma]: and socialism, stop quote, where you kind of point out that the decisions about what

00:45:34.320 --> 00:45:38.000
[Amit Varma]: companies should exist, who should make a profit, who is doing a good job of serving

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:42.240
[Amit Varma]: others or whatever, are made by ordinary people, not some central power in that.

00:45:42.240 --> 00:45:46.920
[Guest]: Yeah, look at the way big companies are vulnerable to their consumers.

00:45:46.920 --> 00:45:50.960
[Guest]: You know, if Kohler launches a product and it's not good, then the whole Kohler company

00:45:50.960 --> 00:45:51.960
[Guest]: is in trouble.

00:45:51.960 --> 00:45:57.080
[Guest]: You know, I mean, look at the way big companies have to rush to, you know, if they offend

00:45:57.080 --> 00:46:00.960
[Guest]: their consumers, their customers in some way, they're in real trouble quite quickly.

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:05.680
[Guest]: So in a proper commercial system, as long as these big companies don't have the ear

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:10.780
[Guest]: of government and can get defense that way, they are very vulnerable and the people in

00:46:10.780 --> 00:46:15.760
[Guest]: charge are the ordinary people, the customers, which is by the way, one of the reasons I

00:46:15.760 --> 00:46:20.400
[Guest]: never use the word capitalism for this system if I can, because capitalism is a much more

00:46:20.400 --> 00:46:21.480
[Guest]: top-down view.

00:46:21.480 --> 00:46:26.720
[Guest]: I think it's an idea of big capitalists being in charge and I think that's the mistake.

00:46:26.720 --> 00:46:31.080
[Guest]: I think we need to think of it as consumers being in charge of the pull from consumers

00:46:31.080 --> 00:46:34.320
[Guest]: rather than the push from producers.

00:46:34.320 --> 00:46:41.480
[Guest]: That said, through crony capitalism, through the links between business and government,

00:46:41.480 --> 00:46:46.120
[Guest]: it is sometimes possible, of course, for big business to behave in a very heavy-handed

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:55.120
[Guest]: and top-down way and insist that rival small competitors don't get a chance and so on.

00:46:55.120 --> 00:46:59.840
[Guest]: So I think that's, you know, one has to watch out for that.

00:46:59.840 --> 00:47:02.680
[Guest]: But that isn't free commerce.

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:08.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I've heard historians who defend Nehru's sort of Fabian socialist vision say that,

00:47:08.440 --> 00:47:12.440
[Amit Varma]: listen, in the late 40s, he set up, he got a group of industrialists together to form

00:47:12.440 --> 00:47:17.520
[Amit Varma]: what was called the Bombay Plan, to talk about their vision for an independent India, whenever

00:47:17.520 --> 00:47:20.240
[Amit Varma]: India became independent, what the economy should look like.

00:47:20.240 --> 00:47:25.680
[Amit Varma]: And they say that, look, they endorse Nehru's view of a top-down, socialistic planned economy

00:47:25.680 --> 00:47:26.680
[Amit Varma]: model.

00:47:26.680 --> 00:47:30.800
[Amit Varma]: And my reply to that is, of course, they would, they're protecting their markets.

00:47:30.800 --> 00:47:33.600
[Amit Varma]: In an actual free market, no one is protected.

00:47:33.600 --> 00:47:38.080
[Amit Varma]: The government simply doesn't have the power to protect this player or that player and,

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:41.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, and a classic example of how this kind of creative destruction happen is in

00:47:41.400 --> 00:47:45.680
[Amit Varma]: the fact that, say, a company like Kodak, which was such a behemoth a while ago doesn't

00:47:45.680 --> 00:47:47.240
[Amit Varma]: exist anymore.

00:47:47.240 --> 00:47:50.840
[Amit Varma]: And you know, 12 years ago, if you had to buy mobile phones, you know, Nokia was a big

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:56.280
[Amit Varma]: player and people who wanted to send emails on their phone would use Blackberry and look

00:47:56.280 --> 00:48:01.040
[Amit Varma]: what happened, you know, things change so fast, because the consumer is always kind

00:48:01.040 --> 00:48:02.720
[Amit Varma]: of in charge.

00:48:02.720 --> 00:48:07.880
[Amit Varma]: And yet there is this sort of tendency to look at government as a solution for everything

00:48:07.880 --> 00:48:12.840
[Amit Varma]: and I'm going to quote another sort of paragraph which also spoke to me where you say, quote,

00:48:12.840 --> 00:48:20.000
[Amit Varma]: take six basic needs of a human being, food, clothing, health, education, shelter and transport.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:25.160
[Amit Varma]: Roughly speaking, in most countries, the market provides food and clothing, the state provides

00:48:25.160 --> 00:48:29.280
[Amit Varma]: health care and education, while shelter and transport are provided by a mixture of the

00:48:29.280 --> 00:48:30.280
[Amit Varma]: two.

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:32.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, stop quote.

00:48:32.040 --> 00:48:36.160
[Amit Varma]: And what is kind of obvious to anyone listening to this is that look in terms of what the

00:48:36.160 --> 00:48:41.560
[Amit Varma]: market provides in terms of food and clothing, we have like far greater variety than we ever

00:48:41.560 --> 00:48:46.000
[Amit Varma]: did before we get far greater value for money, anyone can kind of afford those.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:49.480
[Amit Varma]: But when it comes to health care and education, which the government provides, it is such

00:48:49.480 --> 00:48:50.480
[Amit Varma]: a mess.

00:48:50.480 --> 00:48:57.200
[Guest]: Yes, I think this is a very striking point, actually, that, you know, it's not immediately

00:48:57.200 --> 00:49:04.640
[Guest]: obvious why we haven't got a National Food Service in the UK and allowed health care

00:49:04.640 --> 00:49:06.200
[Amit Varma]: to be provided by the market.

00:49:06.200 --> 00:49:10.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there are reasons, but it's, you know, health, you never know quite when you're gonna

00:49:10.640 --> 00:49:12.080
[Amit Varma]: need health care, and so on.

00:49:12.080 --> 00:49:15.920
[Amit Varma]: But as you point out, there was a sort of a National Food Service, we've seen that counterfactual

00:49:15.920 --> 00:49:17.120
[Guest]: in the Soviet Union.

00:49:17.120 --> 00:49:22.120
[Guest]: Indeed, and in the UK, we had food rationing, right through in the 1950s, Germany gave up

00:49:22.120 --> 00:49:27.360
[Guest]: food rationing much sooner than Britain, because they saw that if they stopped food rationing,

00:49:27.360 --> 00:49:31.040
[Guest]: supplies would rise to meet demand.

00:49:31.040 --> 00:49:33.080
[Guest]: And Britain kept thinking, no, no, food's still scarce.

00:49:33.080 --> 00:49:35.640
[Guest]: So we're still gonna, well, the reason it was scarce, because you had rationing, you

00:49:35.640 --> 00:49:38.680
[Guest]: know, I mean, it's a circular argument.

00:49:38.680 --> 00:49:46.920
[Guest]: Just look at the way food and clothing are cheap, varied, responsive to demand, and evolving

00:49:46.920 --> 00:49:48.400
[Guest]: all the time.

00:49:48.400 --> 00:49:52.520
[Guest]: Just look at the way health and education tend to get stuck in these ways of dealing

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:56.800
[Guest]: things and tend to be starved of resources, and everybody's complaining that there's an

00:49:56.800 --> 00:49:58.580
[Guest]: off budget, and so on.

00:49:58.580 --> 00:50:02.960
[Guest]: It's no coincidence that on the whole, they are provided by the government, whereas food

00:50:02.960 --> 00:50:05.400
[Guest]: and clothing are provided by the market.

00:50:05.400 --> 00:50:11.000
[Guest]: We need to try and find more market mechanisms to deliver health and education.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:15.960
[Guest]: Now, that doesn't mean we dissolve all government intervention overnight, and some countries

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:20.260
[Guest]: have found quite good ways of government making sure that poor people don't suffer for lack

00:50:20.260 --> 00:50:23.640
[Guest]: of health care or education.

00:50:23.640 --> 00:50:25.760
[Guest]: The obvious thing is a voucher system.

00:50:25.760 --> 00:50:30.320
[Guest]: You know, you essentially say, look, here's a voucher for educational health, go out and

00:50:30.320 --> 00:50:35.760
[Guest]: buy it from whichever provider can provide it for you best, that would provoke a ferment

00:50:35.760 --> 00:50:41.240
[Guest]: of innovation in trying to deliver effective health care and food and education to people.

00:50:41.240 --> 00:50:44.960
[Amit Varma]: For those of my listeners who don't know what a voucher system is, I've had an episode on

00:50:44.960 --> 00:50:50.560
[Amit Varma]: this in the past, I've had different episodes on education, a voucher system basically means

00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:54.520
[Amit Varma]: that the government continues to spend what it is spending on education, but it empowers

00:50:54.520 --> 00:50:55.520
[Amit Varma]: the parents.

00:50:55.520 --> 00:50:59.880
[Amit Varma]: So instead of funding the schools, it gives vouchers to the parents and wherever the parents

00:50:59.880 --> 00:51:04.520
[Amit Varma]: choose to send their kid, that school can encash the voucher, whether it is a government

00:51:04.520 --> 00:51:06.040
[Amit Varma]: school or a private school.

00:51:06.040 --> 00:51:10.440
[Amit Varma]: And parents are really in the best place to make decisions about their children's education

00:51:10.440 --> 00:51:11.440
[Amit Varma]: rather than the state.

00:51:11.440 --> 00:51:15.000
[Amit Varma]: I've got a couple of episodes of this in the past, which will be linked from the page of

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:16.000
[Amit Varma]: this podcast.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:21.640
[Amit Varma]: So you can kind of have a look at that the analog I tend to give to people about you

00:51:21.640 --> 00:51:25.480
[Amit Varma]: know, the difference between private provision and government provision is that back in the

00:51:25.480 --> 00:51:31.120
[Amit Varma]: 1980s, when I was growing up in India, telecom and airlines were government monopolies, you

00:51:31.120 --> 00:51:36.520
[Amit Varma]: had one government telephone company, and it would take up to five years to get a telephone

00:51:36.520 --> 00:51:37.520
[Amit Varma]: connection.

00:51:37.520 --> 00:51:41.200
[Amit Varma]: So if you want to, you know, if you want to telephone today, you get on the waiting list,

00:51:41.200 --> 00:51:42.920
[Amit Varma]: it takes maybe five years.

00:51:42.920 --> 00:51:46.640
[Amit Varma]: And a ditto the one government airline was so expensive, most people couldn't afford

00:51:46.640 --> 00:51:47.640
[Amit Varma]: to travel.

00:51:47.640 --> 00:51:51.040
[Amit Varma]: But those got privatized in the liberalization of the early 90s.

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:56.320
[Amit Varma]: And today, anybody can, you know, buy a phone, which is like ludicrously cheap compared to

00:51:56.320 --> 00:51:58.960
[Amit Varma]: what it was, and you'll get a phone in five minutes today.

00:51:58.960 --> 00:52:01.600
[Amit Varma]: And equally airlines also are extremely cheap.

00:52:01.600 --> 00:52:06.000
[Amit Varma]: But what the government did not allow the private sector to do enough in was, for example,

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:07.440
[Amit Varma]: education and healthcare.

00:52:07.440 --> 00:52:12.200
[Amit Varma]: And the argument with education always is that listen, it's too important to be left

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:13.200
[Amit Varma]: to the market.

00:52:13.200 --> 00:52:18.120
[Guest]: And I would actually argue that dammit, it's too important to be left to the state.

00:52:18.120 --> 00:52:21.480
[Guest]: I think you're exactly right, and you know, we're constantly talking about market failure.

00:52:21.480 --> 00:52:23.520
[Guest]: Well, we need to talk about government failure.

00:52:23.520 --> 00:52:28.960
[Guest]: You know, I mean, the government is chronically bad at delivering certain things.

00:52:28.960 --> 00:52:33.040
[Amit Varma]: And government failure is literally ubiquitous and market failure only tends to happen when

00:52:33.040 --> 00:52:35.920
[Amit Varma]: the government doesn't allow the market to operate.

00:52:35.920 --> 00:52:37.440
[Amit Varma]: On the whole, I think that's true.

00:52:37.440 --> 00:52:38.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:52:38.440 --> 00:52:44.160
[Amit Varma]: Let's let's kind of move on to your next chapter, chapter seven, which is the evolution of technology.

00:52:44.160 --> 00:52:47.720
[Amit Varma]: And again, you wrote a piece in the Wall Street Journal, if I remember correctly, which kind

00:52:47.720 --> 00:52:51.820
[Amit Varma]: of summarise the arguments made in this and this I found really interesting where you

00:52:51.820 --> 00:53:00.600
[Amit Varma]: talk about how technological innovations seem to come about almost as a matter of course.

00:53:00.600 --> 00:53:04.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's not like there was one great inventor who invented something and without him, we

00:53:04.800 --> 00:53:06.840
[Amit Varma]: would not have that invention.

00:53:06.840 --> 00:53:10.200
[Amit Varma]: But it's just like when there is a time for it, they kind of happen, you give an example

00:53:10.200 --> 00:53:14.600
[Amit Varma]: of the light bulb and everyone says that, you know, Edison was the inventor.

00:53:14.600 --> 00:53:18.360
[Amit Varma]: But the point you make is if Edison didn't invent it, it was inevitable someone would

00:53:18.360 --> 00:53:21.040
[Amit Varma]: have because there were 26 simultaneous.

00:53:21.040 --> 00:53:26.020
[Guest]: I think it's either 21 or 23, depending on who you count.

00:53:26.020 --> 00:53:30.520
[Guest]: People who can lay claim, according to Robert Friedel, who's researched this, to have invented

00:53:30.520 --> 00:53:33.420
[Guest]: the light bulb independently of Edison.

00:53:33.420 --> 00:53:37.120
[Guest]: And there is no question that if Edison had been run over by a tram, we'd still have had

00:53:37.120 --> 00:53:38.240
[Guest]: light bulbs.

00:53:38.240 --> 00:53:42.600
[Guest]: Because the ability to create a vacuum with a vacuum pump, the ability to blow glass,

00:53:42.600 --> 00:53:47.760
[Guest]: the ability to make light with filaments had all been developed.

00:53:47.760 --> 00:53:50.760
[Guest]: And these technologies were bound to come together.

00:53:50.760 --> 00:53:52.440
[Guest]: And you've got lots of people doing it.

00:53:52.440 --> 00:53:55.680
[Guest]: And actually, you find this phenomenon with pretty well every technology that there is

00:53:55.680 --> 00:53:59.560
[Guest]: a phase of simultaneous invention when lots of people arrive at the same idea at the same

00:53:59.560 --> 00:54:01.640
[Guest]: time, because the idea is ripe.

00:54:01.640 --> 00:54:02.640
[Amit Varma]: It's evolved.

00:54:02.640 --> 00:54:08.520
[Guest]: In the late 1930s, computing is sort of inevitable.

00:54:08.520 --> 00:54:11.040
[Guest]: You know, you've got lots of different people trying to do it.

00:54:11.040 --> 00:54:13.320
[Guest]: Some more electronic than others, some more mechanical.

00:54:13.320 --> 00:54:17.420
[Guest]: But you know, they're basically the ideas that come together to make computing are ready

00:54:17.420 --> 00:54:21.080
[Guest]: to marry and mate and produce a new idea.

00:54:21.080 --> 00:54:28.320
[Guest]: And so this makes the changing technology of the world a much more inexorable process

00:54:28.320 --> 00:54:30.160
[Guest]: than we tend to think of it.

00:54:30.160 --> 00:54:34.080
[Guest]: We tend to think, my goodness, if Einstein or Edison hadn't come along, the world would

00:54:34.080 --> 00:54:37.240
[Guest]: have remained stuck in a different state.

00:54:37.240 --> 00:54:39.120
[Guest]: And that's simply not the case.

00:54:39.120 --> 00:54:44.680
[Guest]: There's a paradox here, though, which is that if that's the case, then why didn't we invent

00:54:44.680 --> 00:54:50.640
[Guest]: everything hundreds of years before?

00:54:50.640 --> 00:54:53.720
[Guest]: And also, why does it happen in certain parts of the world?

00:54:53.720 --> 00:54:59.120
[Guest]: Why does Silicon Valley have to invent the software or whatever?

00:54:59.120 --> 00:55:03.120
[Guest]: Why does Victorian Britain have to develop the steam engine?

00:55:03.120 --> 00:55:05.160
[Guest]: Why does it happen when and where it does?

00:55:05.160 --> 00:55:06.400
[Guest]: And I'm still wrestling with those.

00:55:06.400 --> 00:55:10.760
[Guest]: And actually, that's going to be a big part of my next book is writing a book on innovation

00:55:10.760 --> 00:55:13.960
[Guest]: to try and understand this process.

00:55:13.960 --> 00:55:17.240
[Guest]: But the idea, it has to be seen as evolutionary.

00:55:17.240 --> 00:55:22.400
[Guest]: It's the combination of ideas, the recombination of ideas, and they turn into new ideas as

00:55:22.400 --> 00:55:23.920
[Guest]: a result.

00:55:23.920 --> 00:55:30.240
[Guest]: And Kevin Kelly has a wonderful book, which he writes about, which is called What Technology

00:55:30.240 --> 00:55:31.240
[Guest]: Wants.

00:55:31.240 --> 00:55:33.640
[Guest]: And he's trying to turn it upside down and say, look, it's technology that's doing the

00:55:33.640 --> 00:55:36.440
[Guest]: evolving and it's choosing the inventors to do it.

00:55:36.440 --> 00:55:38.720
[Guest]: And actually, that's a surprisingly fruitful way of looking at it.

00:55:38.720 --> 00:55:41.920
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's a great sentence in your chapter, which says the same thing, quote,

00:55:41.920 --> 00:55:47.200
[Amit Varma]: we ride rather than drive the innovation wave, technology will find its inventors rather

00:55:47.200 --> 00:55:52.080
[Amit Varma]: than vice versa, stop quote, and you also use this to sort of make the point that, you

00:55:52.080 --> 00:55:57.440
[Amit Varma]: know, we should kind of rethink patents, therefore, because patents tend to favor the lucky guy

00:55:57.440 --> 00:56:00.640
[Amit Varma]: who just happened to file the papers first.

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:05.440
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, technology, in a sense, is inevitable, it's evolving, it's going to happen anyway.

00:56:05.440 --> 00:56:09.040
[Guest]: Well, I do think that intellectual property is overrated.

00:56:09.040 --> 00:56:13.040
[Guest]: The more you study it, the more you see that it's actually being used for exactly the opposite

00:56:13.040 --> 00:56:14.680
[Guest]: purpose for which it's intended.

00:56:14.680 --> 00:56:17.700
[Guest]: It's intended to incentivize innovation.

00:56:17.700 --> 00:56:22.440
[Guest]: It has tended to morph into a system whereby people keep competitors out and hang on to

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:24.960
[Guest]: monopolies longer than they deserve to.

00:56:24.960 --> 00:56:29.840
[Guest]: You've obviously got to have a balance here, because you can't simply throw open to all

00:56:29.840 --> 00:56:34.400
[Guest]: competitors something that you've, through regulation, insisted be tested very carefully

00:56:34.400 --> 00:56:38.600
[Guest]: before it's released on the market, like a drug or something like that.

00:56:38.600 --> 00:56:39.720
[Guest]: And it's the same with copyright.

00:56:39.720 --> 00:56:46.000
[Guest]: I think the metaphor that we use for intellectual property for copyright or patents is wrong.

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:52.520
[Guest]: It's not a property, because the thing about physical property, a building or a house or

00:56:52.520 --> 00:56:59.400
[Guest]: a field or something, is that I can own it and prevent anyone else having access to it.

00:56:59.400 --> 00:57:02.120
[Guest]: But if I were to share it, then I lose something.

00:57:02.120 --> 00:57:07.520
[Guest]: Then somebody else is using my house and we can't both live in the house at the same time.

00:57:07.520 --> 00:57:14.060
[Guest]: Whereas with an idea, you can give it away and still have it, although you're less likely

00:57:14.060 --> 00:57:17.000
[Guest]: to be able to make money out of its monopoly.

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:21.680
[Guest]: So actually, the way Paul Romer talks about this kind of thing with his endogenous growth

00:57:21.680 --> 00:57:27.080
[Guest]: theory is that by being the first mover, by getting there first, you get a brief monopoly

00:57:27.080 --> 00:57:28.080
[Guest]: anyway.

00:57:28.080 --> 00:57:31.640
[Guest]: You've got to figure out how to put this together, and that's enough to keep you going.

00:57:31.640 --> 00:57:36.440
[Guest]: And if you look at most of the software industry, it hasn't been made possible by patents.

00:57:36.440 --> 00:57:41.480
[Guest]: It's been made possible by people getting there, being smart, doing it first, and doing

00:57:41.480 --> 00:57:42.480
[Guest]: it well.

00:57:42.480 --> 00:57:49.840
[Guest]: You know, Apple and Amazon and people like that don't rely on patents to keep their competitive

00:57:49.840 --> 00:57:50.840
[Guest]: edge.

00:57:50.840 --> 00:57:52.280
[Guest]: They rely on innovation.

00:57:52.280 --> 00:57:54.320
[Amit Varma]: And that's the way we should be thinking about the world.

00:57:54.320 --> 00:57:56.560
[Amit Varma]: Chapter eight is called Evolution of the Mind.

00:57:56.560 --> 00:58:02.400
[Amit Varma]: And I found it really interesting and counterintuitive because people think that if there is one

00:58:02.400 --> 00:58:08.240
[Amit Varma]: thing that is top-down, it is surely the self, that I am in charge and my body and my brain

00:58:08.240 --> 00:58:10.360
[Amit Varma]: are under my control.

00:58:10.360 --> 00:58:16.960
[Amit Varma]: And I've recently sort of come to rethink free will, and I pretty much don't see how

00:58:16.960 --> 00:58:17.960
[Amit Varma]: free will can be there.

00:58:17.960 --> 00:58:22.160
[Amit Varma]: I kind of follow in the path of Sam Harris and Robert Sapolsky in this.

00:58:22.160 --> 00:58:26.600
[Amit Varma]: And your chapter does a fascinating overview of that whole debate and shows that how a

00:58:26.600 --> 00:58:30.120
[Amit Varma]: lot of what we think we are doing, we aren't actually doing it.

00:58:30.120 --> 00:58:32.840
[Amit Varma]: We are sort of, the causation is sort of the other way around.

00:58:32.840 --> 00:58:37.080
[Guest]: Yes, this is a very different chapter to the rest of the book, and I delve into philosophy

00:58:37.080 --> 00:58:42.000
[Guest]: and as always with the free will argument, and I've wrestled with it in previous books

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:47.080
[Guest]: before, I'm never entirely satisfied that I've reached the right answer.

00:58:47.080 --> 00:58:51.720
[Guest]: But I do think that we have to move away from thinking of a homunculus in the middle of

00:58:51.720 --> 00:58:56.560
[Guest]: our brain in charge, sitting at a little control.

00:58:56.560 --> 00:59:00.440
[Guest]: In the movie Men in Black, they open up a corpse and they find this little person sitting

00:59:00.440 --> 00:59:06.640
[Guest]: in there with a control panel, and of course, that's not what's going on.

00:59:06.640 --> 00:59:12.960
[Guest]: And when it comes to things like responsibility for your behavior, for example, somebody who

00:59:12.960 --> 00:59:18.640
[Guest]: commits crimes and it turns out to be a tumor in their head that's causing it, that sort

00:59:18.640 --> 00:59:23.800
[Guest]: of, we're clearly then saying, okay, so it wasn't you that was responsible, it was the

00:59:23.800 --> 00:59:24.800
[Guest]: tumor.

00:59:24.800 --> 00:59:25.800
[Guest]: Well, what is you?

00:59:25.800 --> 00:59:28.320
[Guest]: You know, I mean, who would you be?

00:59:28.320 --> 00:59:34.440
[Guest]: And actually, we need to turn this over and start thinking it the other way up, you know,

00:59:34.440 --> 00:59:38.640
[Guest]: that after all, we know that the mind is simply the product of the brain, there's nothing

00:59:38.640 --> 00:59:44.880
[Guest]: else in there, you know, there's no, we're never going to find some sort of secret source

00:59:44.880 --> 00:59:45.880
[Guest]: called the soul.

00:59:45.880 --> 00:59:53.040
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's always been fascinating to me how personality and identity are so contingent.

00:59:53.040 --> 00:59:56.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, you tweak the chemical balance of your brain a little bit, or you, you know,

00:59:56.640 --> 00:59:59.720
[Amit Varma]: if there's a tumor somewhere, you suddenly become an entirely different person.

00:59:59.720 --> 01:00:04.480
[Amit Varma]: And I think this should introduce humility in a lot of people about who they really are.

01:00:04.480 --> 01:00:05.480
[Guest]: Correct.

01:00:05.480 --> 01:00:07.600
[Guest]: So at three in the morning, I'm a pessimist.

01:00:07.600 --> 01:00:10.000
[Guest]: At noon in the daytime, I'm an optimist.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:14.440
[Guest]: I don't, you know, it's nothing to do with the world, it's to do with the brain chemistry

01:00:14.440 --> 01:00:15.440
[Guest]: of my head.

01:00:15.440 --> 01:00:16.440
[Amit Varma]: You're a rational optimist.

01:00:16.440 --> 01:00:19.440
[Guest]: I am indeed a rational optimist.

01:00:19.440 --> 01:00:20.440
[Guest]: Right.

01:00:20.440 --> 01:00:22.840
[Amit Varma]: I know we are running kind of short of time, I need to wind this up.

01:00:22.840 --> 01:00:26.560
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of go through the different chapters.

01:00:26.560 --> 01:00:32.280
[Amit Varma]: Your ninth chapter is the evolution of personality, where you refer to that classic book by Judith

01:00:32.280 --> 01:00:35.920
[Amit Varma]: Rich Harris, A Nurture Assumption, you know, one of my favorite books and one of the most

01:00:35.920 --> 01:00:38.400
[Guest]: important social science books of the 20th century.

01:00:38.400 --> 01:00:39.400
[Guest]: Correct.

01:00:39.400 --> 01:00:40.400
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you.

01:00:40.400 --> 01:00:46.980
[Amit Varma]: She kind of, I mean, her conclusions essentially are that, to quote you, differences in personality

01:00:46.980 --> 01:00:51.680
[Amit Varma]: are formed roughly half by the direct and indirect effects of genes, and roughly half

01:00:51.680 --> 01:00:55.920
[Amit Varma]: by something else, which did not include the home environment at all.

01:00:55.920 --> 01:00:56.920
[Guest]: Unquote.

01:00:56.920 --> 01:00:57.920
[Guest]: Isn't this amazing?

01:00:57.920 --> 01:01:02.120
[Guest]: And Robert Plomin has now written a book called blueprint, which makes exactly the same argument

01:01:02.120 --> 01:01:04.760
[Guest]: with it with even better data.

01:01:04.760 --> 01:01:08.720
[Guest]: And this is a remarkable discovery and an unexpected one, I have to say, I'm surprised

01:01:08.720 --> 01:01:13.520
[Guest]: by it, that our parents are not a great influence on our personalities.

01:01:13.520 --> 01:01:20.120
[Guest]: Our personalities are the product of our genes to a large extent, and also to sort of experiences

01:01:20.120 --> 01:01:26.200
[Guest]: which can often be quite ephemeral or quite accidental things that happen in our lives.

01:01:26.200 --> 01:01:31.360
[Guest]: Plomin gives the example of Charles Darwin, who was selected for the Beagle voyage by

01:01:31.360 --> 01:01:37.800
[Guest]: the captain who liked the shape of his nose, and he believed in phrenology that your nose

01:01:37.800 --> 01:01:41.120
[Guest]: told you something about your personality, and he thought this would be a good person

01:01:41.120 --> 01:01:46.000
[Guest]: to share a cabin with for five years because of the shape of his nose.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:50.120
[Guest]: Now, because of going on the Beagle, Charles Darwin, obviously his personality must be

01:01:50.120 --> 01:01:57.000
[Guest]: influenced by that as is, of course, his future life course, et cetera, an incredibly accidental

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:00.000
[Guest]: thing that should shape his life.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:02.720
[Guest]: Some people feel threatened by this, what do you mean I'm just a product of my genes?

01:02:02.720 --> 01:02:05.880
[Guest]: I would like to be the product of my family.

01:02:05.880 --> 01:02:10.360
[Guest]: Well, actually, being the product of your genes means you're you, you're not what someone

01:02:10.360 --> 01:02:12.120
[Guest]: else has made you.

01:02:12.120 --> 01:02:14.720
[Guest]: And that actually is a very liberating thought, I think.

01:02:14.720 --> 01:02:15.720
[Amit Varma]: Although it's an accident.

01:02:15.720 --> 01:02:16.720
[Amit Varma]: It's an accident.

01:02:16.720 --> 01:02:17.720
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:02:17.720 --> 01:02:18.720
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:02:18.720 --> 01:02:24.520
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the really interesting revelations in this chapter, interesting factoid,

01:02:24.520 --> 01:02:31.520
[Amit Varma]: if I may call it that, and that's another term that's evolved factoid, was that people's

01:02:31.520 --> 01:02:37.200
[Amit Varma]: incomes, men's incomes are actually determined by how tall they are, taller men tend to earn

01:02:37.200 --> 01:02:38.200
[Amit Varma]: more.

01:02:38.200 --> 01:02:40.440
[Amit Varma]: But this is a height at the age of 16.

01:02:40.440 --> 01:02:42.480
[Amit Varma]: Not their height at the age of 30.

01:02:42.480 --> 01:02:43.480
[Guest]: Isn't that fascinating?

01:02:43.480 --> 01:02:44.480
[Guest]: I know.

01:02:44.480 --> 01:02:45.480
[Guest]: Mind blowing.

01:02:45.480 --> 01:02:48.880
[Guest]: I'm very tall, but I wasn't particularly tall at 16.

01:02:48.880 --> 01:02:56.880
[Amit Varma]: So I'd be richer if I was doing fine.

01:02:56.880 --> 01:03:01.200
[Amit Varma]: Your next chapter is again, extremely fascinating to me, which is the evolution of education.

01:03:01.200 --> 01:03:05.400
[Amit Varma]: Education is something that's always kind of been top down.

01:03:05.400 --> 01:03:10.640
[Amit Varma]: And we this is particularly sort of a disturbing subject for me, because in India, what we

01:03:10.640 --> 01:03:13.800
[Amit Varma]: right now have is education system has always been buggered.

01:03:13.800 --> 01:03:18.480
[Amit Varma]: But now what we have is our demographic dividend, what people call it is really a demographic

01:03:18.480 --> 01:03:23.680
[Amit Varma]: disaster, where you have more than a million people a month coming into the workforce without

01:03:23.680 --> 01:03:24.680
[Amit Varma]: jobs.

01:03:24.680 --> 01:03:31.120
[Amit Varma]: And one of the key sort of problems there is that not only are there no jobs for them,

01:03:31.120 --> 01:03:33.080
[Amit Varma]: they don't even have any skills.

01:03:33.080 --> 01:03:38.200
[Amit Varma]: Our education system doesn't even give them the skills to go out there and do something.

01:03:38.200 --> 01:03:44.400
[Amit Varma]: And there's this massive mismatch between demand and supply, that the education supply

01:03:44.400 --> 01:03:48.800
[Amit Varma]: is not providing the kind of skills that the markets actually need.

01:03:48.800 --> 01:03:54.360
[Amit Varma]: And this is, to me a classic fault of it being top down and markets not allowed to operate.

01:03:54.360 --> 01:04:01.440
[Guest]: And, you know, I trace this back with the help of the wonderful Indian thinker about

01:04:01.440 --> 01:04:07.640
[Guest]: this, Sugata Mitra, to the idea that the British Empire decided it needed clerks who would

01:04:07.640 --> 01:04:12.960
[Guest]: be the same in Canada and India, so that the people in the center could understand, could

01:04:12.960 --> 01:04:13.960
[Guest]: treat them the same.

01:04:13.960 --> 01:04:16.880
[Guest]: And so they needed to be cogs in a machine.

01:04:16.880 --> 01:04:22.360
[Guest]: And so they needed to give them this very systematic, similar education, a lot of which

01:04:22.360 --> 01:04:26.600
[Guest]: is still found around the world and we, you know, here we are in the 21st century with

01:04:26.600 --> 01:04:32.200
[Guest]: all sorts of technologies and we've not really changed the way we educate, enabling children

01:04:32.200 --> 01:04:33.200
[Guest]: to learn.

01:04:33.200 --> 01:04:36.760
[Guest]: And that often means using new technology is very important.

01:04:36.760 --> 01:04:40.900
[Guest]: And I also, I think, touch on James Tooley's work in Hyderabad and other places where he

01:04:40.900 --> 01:04:45.660
[Guest]: finds that actually the people are voting with their feet and seeking out low-cost private

01:04:45.660 --> 01:04:52.720
[Guest]: education of an extremely cheap kind, but rather than going for the state provision.

01:04:52.720 --> 01:04:56.640
[Guest]: And this shows how there is demand out there for change.

01:04:56.640 --> 01:05:00.740
[Guest]: It's interesting to hear that in India you're just as frustrated by the mismatch between

01:05:00.740 --> 01:05:06.580
[Guest]: what schools are doing and what the workforce is demanding, the employment world is demanding.

01:05:06.580 --> 01:05:09.000
[Guest]: We feel the same in Britain anyway.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:13.640
[Amit Varma]: No, and one quote that really spoke to me was you quoted a gentleman named Albert Shankar

01:05:13.640 --> 01:05:18.380
[Amit Varma]: and he said, start quote, it's no surprise that our school system doesn't improve.

01:05:18.380 --> 01:05:23.040
[Amit Varma]: It resembles a communist economy more than our own market economy.

01:05:23.040 --> 01:05:24.040
[Guest]: It's correct, isn't it?

01:05:24.040 --> 01:05:28.560
[Guest]: I mean, you know, it really is a centrally planned system, most education systems in

01:05:28.560 --> 01:05:29.560
[Unknown]: most countries.

01:05:29.560 --> 01:05:33.280
[Guest]: And he was a union official, actually, American union official.

01:05:33.280 --> 01:05:39.560
[Amit Varma]: Your 11th chapter is about the evolution of population, about the harm that Malthusian

01:05:39.560 --> 01:05:41.320
[Amit Varma]: thinking does.

01:05:41.320 --> 01:05:44.720
[Amit Varma]: What I'll do is, because we're kind of running out of time and you need to check out of your

01:05:44.720 --> 01:05:48.240
[Amit Varma]: room where we are recording this, I'll skip over the rest of your chapters, I'll mention

01:05:48.240 --> 01:05:50.960
[Amit Varma]: them and just end with a couple of broad questions.

01:05:50.960 --> 01:05:55.760
[Amit Varma]: Your 11th chapter is the evolution of population, your 12th chapter is the evolution of leadership,

01:05:55.760 --> 01:06:01.360
[Amit Varma]: where you question Thomas Carlyle's great man theory, and, you know, which is again

01:06:01.360 --> 01:06:03.040
[Amit Varma]: extremely fascinating.

01:06:03.040 --> 01:06:06.200
[Amit Varma]: And actually, I do want to stop for a moment on chapter 13.

01:06:06.200 --> 01:06:08.360
[Amit Varma]: That's the evolution of government.

01:06:08.360 --> 01:06:14.200
[Amit Varma]: And you begin the chapter by writing about how gangs arise in prisons and what that sort

01:06:14.200 --> 01:06:15.200
[Guest]: of indicates.

01:06:15.200 --> 01:06:16.200
[Guest]: Can you tell us?

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:24.260
[Guest]: Yeah, no, this is fascinating work that shows that within prisons, people tend to self organize

01:06:24.260 --> 01:06:26.160
[Guest]: into gangs.

01:06:26.160 --> 01:06:32.160
[Guest]: And the gangs then impose order on the prisons and tend to suppress violence, actually, because

01:06:32.160 --> 01:06:36.760
[Amit Varma]: in male prisons where the population goes over a certain size, and therefore some kind

01:06:36.760 --> 01:06:38.480
[Amit Varma]: of government is needed.

01:06:38.480 --> 01:06:39.480
[Guest]: Correct.

01:06:39.480 --> 01:06:40.480
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:06:40.480 --> 01:06:42.640
[Guest]: And in fact, it's starting to happen in female prisons now, which are on the whole once a

01:06:42.640 --> 01:06:45.800
[Guest]: population reaches exactly, yeah.

01:06:45.800 --> 01:06:51.840
[Guest]: And I think this is an analogy for what happened in societies as to when government spontaneously

01:06:51.840 --> 01:06:53.000
[Guest]: arose.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:56.840
[Guest]: Because after all, what is government, it is a monopoly on violence, essentially, that's

01:06:56.840 --> 01:07:03.520
[Guest]: the sort of core point of government is to say, we will have all the weapons or most

01:07:03.520 --> 01:07:10.120
[Guest]: of the weapons ourselves, and we will have the right to violently or forcibly suppress

01:07:10.120 --> 01:07:11.120
[Guest]: certain behavior.

01:07:11.120 --> 01:07:13.840
[Guest]: No one else has that right.

01:07:13.840 --> 01:07:22.720
[Guest]: And once you've got that, you can live your life free from the threat of being arbitrarily

01:07:22.720 --> 01:07:24.960
[Guest]: assassinated by one of your rivals.

01:07:24.960 --> 01:07:28.880
[Guest]: But of course, you've now got the threat of being arbitrarily assassinated by your government,

01:07:28.880 --> 01:07:34.000
[Guest]: if it takes against you, as indeed, people have experienced in communist and fascist

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:35.640
[Amit Varma]: regimes.

01:07:35.640 --> 01:07:40.360
[Amit Varma]: And the government can do a variety of things, which if someone else did would be criminal,

01:07:40.360 --> 01:07:43.000
[Amit Varma]: but the government because of the government, they can do it, they can abduct you, they

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:45.000
[Guest]: can steal from you, they can just do whatever they want.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:46.000
[Guest]: It's extraordinary, isn't it?

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:48.000
[Guest]: They can tax you, you know,

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:49.000
[Amit Varma]: I did say steal free.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:50.000
[Unknown]: You did say steal free.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:53.360
[Guest]: And they never say thank you either when they do that.

01:07:53.360 --> 01:07:54.360
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:07:54.360 --> 01:07:57.120
[Amit Varma]: So there's a great paragraph of yours, which of course, I'm going to quote, which is government

01:07:57.120 --> 01:08:03.360
[Amit Varma]: began as a mafia protection racket, claiming a monopoly on violence and extracting a rent

01:08:03.360 --> 01:08:07.920
[Amit Varma]: tax in return for protecting his citizens from depredation by outsiders.

01:08:07.920 --> 01:08:10.120
[Amit Varma]: This is the origin of almost all government.

01:08:10.120 --> 01:08:15.200
[Amit Varma]: And today's mafia protection rackets are all in the process of evolving into government

01:08:15.200 --> 01:08:16.200
[Amit Varma]: stop code.

01:08:16.200 --> 01:08:19.440
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of very interesting how in a democracy like ours, for example, what an

01:08:19.440 --> 01:08:24.560
[Amit Varma]: election amounts to is you have different criminal gangs vying to be the one legal mafia

01:08:24.560 --> 01:08:27.640
[Guest]: for a period of five years or whatever, correct.

01:08:27.640 --> 01:08:31.520
[Guest]: It's a very good way of looking at it.

01:08:31.520 --> 01:08:36.720
[Guest]: You know, there's a guy who stands up there says, I want to spend other people's money

01:08:36.720 --> 01:08:37.720
[Guest]: for five years.

01:08:37.720 --> 01:08:42.800
[Guest]: I want to be in charge of spending other people's money on a massive scale for five years.

01:08:42.800 --> 01:08:46.800
[Guest]: And we are expected to find him a moral leader.

01:08:46.800 --> 01:08:53.040
[Guest]: You know, why are we surprised when we end up with people like Donald Trump in charge

01:08:53.040 --> 01:08:54.040
[Guest]: of the world?

01:08:54.040 --> 01:08:58.600
[Guest]: If that's if that's the recipe way, which we're choosing people, essentially, you will

01:08:58.600 --> 01:09:04.040
[Amit Varma]: have the most sociopathic power hungry people coming to power anyway, of course, yeah.

01:09:04.040 --> 01:09:10.120
[Amit Varma]: And you end the chapter with by talking about, quote, the equally mistaken belief that fascism

01:09:10.120 --> 01:09:11.800
[Amit Varma]: and communism are opposites.

01:09:11.800 --> 01:09:17.640
[Amit Varma]: In reality, they are closely related historical competitors for the same constituents.

01:09:17.640 --> 01:09:18.640
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:09:18.640 --> 01:09:19.640
[Guest]: And they're both top down.

01:09:19.640 --> 01:09:20.640
[Guest]: Yes.

01:09:20.640 --> 01:09:24.200
[Guest]: And I think there's much a lot of people realize that there's much more similarity between

01:09:24.200 --> 01:09:27.040
[Guest]: the different types of totalitarian regime.

01:09:27.040 --> 01:09:30.840
[Guest]: And actually, if you look at the origins of fascism, you know, Mussolini was a communist

01:09:30.840 --> 01:09:33.000
[Guest]: before he was a fascist.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:37.080
[Guest]: Hitler was a socialist before he was a Nazi and so on.

01:09:37.080 --> 01:09:41.560
[Guest]: And you know, they end up being very, very similar.

01:09:41.560 --> 01:09:48.080
[Guest]: The one difference is that the fascist regimes tend to allow private business to depredate

01:09:48.080 --> 01:09:53.440
[Guest]: on their behalf, whereas communist regimes tend to encourage state owned businesses to

01:09:53.440 --> 01:09:55.400
[Guest]: depredate on their behalf.

01:09:55.400 --> 01:09:58.280
[Amit Varma]: But that's about the difference of the structure of coercion.

01:09:58.280 --> 01:10:03.020
[Amit Varma]: But the bottom line there in both cases is coercion and top down mass coercion.

01:10:03.020 --> 01:10:06.920
[Guest]: And of course, communism is slightly better at pretending that it's acting on behalf of

01:10:06.920 --> 01:10:08.680
[Guest]: ordinary people.

01:10:08.680 --> 01:10:09.680
[Guest]: But it isn't really.

01:10:09.680 --> 01:10:13.760
[Guest]: I mean, it ends up being an incredibly unequal society in terms of access to resources.

01:10:13.760 --> 01:10:19.280
[Amit Varma]: Your last three chapters are about the evolution of religion, the evolution of money, the evolution

01:10:19.280 --> 01:10:23.480
[Amit Varma]: of the Internet, all really fascinating, but I don't want to hold you up now.

01:10:23.480 --> 01:10:26.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'll end with these broad questions.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:32.480
[Amit Varma]: One of which is that, why is it that people crave top down explanations for everything?

01:10:32.480 --> 01:10:33.840
[Amit Varma]: Is it the way we've evolved?

01:10:33.840 --> 01:10:36.720
[Amit Varma]: Is it possibly selected for?

01:10:36.720 --> 01:10:39.920
[Guest]: It's a difficult question this and I don't really know the answer.

01:10:39.920 --> 01:10:46.920
[Guest]: And it talks about the intentional stance, which is the tendency to see agency behind

01:10:46.920 --> 01:10:47.920
[Guest]: everything.

01:10:47.920 --> 01:10:52.200
[Guest]: So if there's a thunderstorm, we assume that it's a God.

01:10:52.200 --> 01:10:56.560
[Guest]: If there's an earthquake, we assume we're being punished for our sins or something like

01:10:56.560 --> 01:10:58.100
[Guest]: that.

01:10:58.100 --> 01:11:02.140
[Guest]: And perhaps there is an evolutionary psychology explanation for this.

01:11:02.140 --> 01:11:07.520
[Guest]: Because if you walk around thinking the world is full of accidental happenings that don't

01:11:07.520 --> 01:11:14.440
[Guest]: have any agency behind them, you will occasionally miss out on insights into how your fellow

01:11:14.440 --> 01:11:16.760
[Guest]: human beings are behaving.

01:11:16.760 --> 01:11:22.440
[Guest]: So if a rock hits you on the back of the head as you're walking down a path, you will think,

01:11:22.440 --> 01:11:23.440
[Guest]: oh, well, I was unlucky.

01:11:23.440 --> 01:11:26.720
[Guest]: A rock flew off the ground and hit me in the back of the head.

01:11:26.720 --> 01:11:30.960
[Guest]: Whereas if you turn around and say, right, who threw that?

01:11:30.960 --> 01:11:36.320
[Guest]: You've got a point, actually, that you're probably better off having a hair trigger

01:11:36.320 --> 01:11:39.680
[Guest]: for assuming intentional actions.

01:11:39.680 --> 01:11:43.680
[Guest]: It probably won't get you into too much trouble, and it will enable you to be.

01:11:43.680 --> 01:11:49.480
[Guest]: But it leads to what is essentially living in a state of constant conspiracy theory.

01:11:49.480 --> 01:11:50.840
[Guest]: That's what we are as human beings.

01:11:50.840 --> 01:11:54.400
[Guest]: We're constantly in a conspiracy theory that God created the world, that God is running

01:11:54.400 --> 01:11:56.560
[Guest]: the world, or that government is in charge.

01:11:56.560 --> 01:11:58.040
[Guest]: These are conspiracy theories.

01:11:58.040 --> 01:12:03.760
[Amit Varma]: And I guess the world is so complex and mind-boggling that it's natural to imagine that this is

01:12:03.760 --> 01:12:07.560
[Amit Varma]: selected for that we look for simple narratives to explain the world.

01:12:07.560 --> 01:12:11.880
[Amit Varma]: And whatever narrative fits as many of the facts as there are, that narrative will make

01:12:11.880 --> 01:12:13.440
[Amit Varma]: the most sense to us.

01:12:13.440 --> 01:12:15.320
[Amit Varma]: And a top-down narrative can fit everything.

01:12:15.320 --> 01:12:19.880
[Amit Varma]: So you make sense of the world originally by invoking a God early on, it's their nature

01:12:19.880 --> 01:12:24.320
[Amit Varma]: gods and then the gods themselves evolve as religion evolves.

01:12:24.320 --> 01:12:29.080
[Guest]: Which of course is why this book has not been terribly successful, is because this isn't

01:12:29.080 --> 01:12:33.480
[Guest]: something everyone really wants to hear.

01:12:33.480 --> 01:12:35.800
[Guest]: I'm fighting against human nature here.

01:12:35.800 --> 01:12:38.760
[Guest]: I'm trying to get people to reject their instincts.

01:12:38.760 --> 01:12:42.280
[Amit Varma]: Instead of the evolution of everything, you should have called your book the design of

01:12:42.280 --> 01:12:43.280
[Amit Varma]: everything.

01:12:43.280 --> 01:12:44.280
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:12:44.280 --> 01:12:45.280
[Amit Varma]: And then I might have sold more copies.

01:12:45.280 --> 01:12:46.280
[Amit Varma]: Let me ask my last question.

01:12:46.280 --> 01:12:51.160
[Amit Varma]: Given the sort of resistance to our ideas of spontaneous order and natural selection

01:12:51.160 --> 01:12:56.680
[Amit Varma]: and all these beautiful processes which explain the world, what is it that gives you sort

01:12:56.680 --> 01:13:01.920
[Amit Varma]: of hope and despair, it's a two part question, about the future of human society, about the

01:13:01.920 --> 01:13:04.400
[Amit Varma]: evolution of human society, so to say?

01:13:04.400 --> 01:13:10.120
[Guest]: Well, the track record of the last 200 years is the rational, behind my rational optimism,

01:13:10.120 --> 01:13:15.960
[Guest]: that we have sufficiently managed to embrace enlightened ideas to unleash a torrent of

01:13:15.960 --> 01:13:20.080
[Guest]: innovation that has improved the lives of millions of people.

01:13:20.080 --> 01:13:21.360
[Guest]: And it's continuing.

01:13:21.360 --> 01:13:26.000
[Guest]: And it's quite hard to put that genie back in the bottle, that despite ourselves, despite

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:31.040
[Guest]: our intentional stance, despite our top-down view of the world, nonetheless, in our interactions

01:13:31.040 --> 01:13:38.640
[Guest]: we do enough bottom-up things to cause this increasing amelioration of the state of human

01:13:38.640 --> 01:13:40.400
[Guest]: beings.

01:13:40.400 --> 01:13:50.400
[Guest]: And actually, in order to do bad things with technology, in order to release computer viruses

01:13:50.400 --> 01:13:58.520
[Guest]: or anything, you have to on the whole be secretive, cut yourself off from the ferment of experimentation

01:13:58.520 --> 01:14:02.240
[Guest]: and bottom-up stuff that is driving the good stuff in the world.

01:14:02.240 --> 01:14:06.760
[Guest]: So on the whole, I think the good will win out for that reason, because it can happen

01:14:06.760 --> 01:14:11.440
[Guest]: in the sunshine, whereas bad stuff has to happen in the dark.

01:14:11.440 --> 01:14:14.240
[Guest]: And that gives me some hope for the future.

01:14:14.240 --> 01:14:20.120
[Guest]: But, you know, somebody sitting in the Roman Empire or just before the First World War

01:14:20.120 --> 01:14:22.880
[Guest]: or something might have said something similar.

01:14:22.880 --> 01:14:27.000
[Guest]: So I might be the man who's fallen out of the skyscraper and says, so far, so good as

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:28.600
